is a shared-context HUB with in-hub routing\",\n\n  Line 182:       \"statement\": \"The optimal sk-design taxonomy is 6 children: direction, foundations, motion, critique, system, presentation.\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion/research/lineages/opus48-claude2/deep-research-config.json:\n  Line 2:   \"topic\": \"Highest-leverage reference and asset expansions for the five sk-design sub-skills (design-interface, design-foundations, design-motion, design-audit, design-md-generator), grounded in the 154 corpus research, the gap-analysis, and the 43-entry external corpus. Per-mode expansion matrix: inventory gaps, prioritized additions (type/title/why/sources/effort), and an explicit do-NOT-add list honoring the if-effective bar.\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion/research/lineages/opus48-claude2/deep-research-findings-registry.json:\n  Line 21:     \"Q3 design-motion expansion matrix\",\n\n  Line 31:     {\"id\": \"KF5\", \"mode\": \"motion\", \"text\": \"Gesture basics covered; real 08e gap is the emil frequency-decision restraint gate\", \"evidence\": \"design-motion/references/micro_interactions.md:61-66; external/emil-design-eng.md:62-79\"},\n\n  Line 32:     {\"id\": \"KF6\", \"mode\": \"audit\", \"text\": \"No model-tell catalog; impeccable supplies a concrete Codex/Gemini/2026-general one (AU-R1, highest leverage)\", \"evidence\": \"external/impeccable.md:42-44,69-70,100-108\"},\n\n  Line 44:     {\"approach\": \"Gesture basics into motion\", \"reason\": \"Already in micro_interactions §4\", \"iteration\": 3},\n\n  Line 45:     {\"approach\": \"Motion-performance review into motion\", \"reason\": \"Audit boundary\", \"iteration\": 3},\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research/research/lineages/gpt55fast/deep-research-findings-registry.json:\n  Line 7:       \"answer\": \"Use six children: strategy, interface-craft, interaction-motion, system-reference, critique-quality, and delivery-ops.\",\n\n  Line 26:       \"finding\": \"The corpus explicitly favors routing to the smallest useful context rather than loading a broad design blob.\",\n\n  Line 48:       \"reason\": \"Over-fragments the family and conflicts with smallest-context routing.\",\n\n  Line 53:       \"reason\": \"Creates high coupling across extraction, craft, critique, motion, and delivery contracts.\",\n\n  Line 58:       \"reason\": \"Existing cross-skill references and user routing name current skills.\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion/research/lineages/gpt55fast/deep-research-findings-registry.json:\n  Line 13:       \"mode\": \"shared/interface/audit/foundations/motion\",\n\n  Line 16:       \"summary\": \"A shared register should gate density, motion, color, copy, and anti-slop decisions before mode-specific references branch.\",\n\n  Line 37:       \"mode\": \"design-motion\",\n\n  Line 41:       \"sources\": [\".opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:289\", \".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/mastering-animate-presence.md:21\", \".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external/fixing-motion-performance.md:52\"]\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion/research/.smoke-archive/lineages/opus48-claude2/deep-research-config.json:\n  Line 2:   \"topic\": \"Highest-leverage reference and asset expansions for the five sk-design sub-skills (design-interface, design-foundations, design-motion, design-audit, design-md-generator), grounded in the 154 corpus research and the 43-entry external corpus.\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion/research/.smoke-archive/lineages/opus48-claude2/deep-research-findings-registry.json:\n  Line 23:       \"why\": \"Highest-leverage missing reference; gates motion budget, density, accent dosage, and the anti-slop bar; dependency of the transform-verb, model-tells, remediation, mock-content, and pre-flight adds (gap 05).\",\n\n  Line 25:       \"consumedBy\": [\"interface\", \"audit\", \"foundations(dosage)\", \"motion(budget)\"]\n\n  Line 55:       \"sources\": [\"external/impeccable.md:100-108\", \"external/impeccable.md:69-71\", \"external/taste-skill.md:595\"]\n\n  Line 79:       \"scope\": \"motion\",\n\n  Line 84:       \"why\": \"gap 08e; the single biggest motion depth gap. emil-design-eng is the corpus's deepest interaction-engineering doc and motion cites none of it; current gesture coverage is one shallow section.\",\n\n  Line 89:       \"scope\": \"motion\",\n\n  Line 90:       \"title\": \"assets/easing_duration_card.md (one-page motion decision card)\",\n\n  Line 94:       \"why\": \"Motion has no assets/. A duration-by-interaction + ease-out-expo curves + never-patterns (no layout-prop animation, no transition:all, no scale(0)) + reduced-motion card is the most-reached-for artifact during a build.\",\n\n  Line 105:       \"sources\": [\"external/redesign-skill.md:78-89\", \"external/taste-skill.md:615\", \"external/taste-skill.md:685\", \"external/impeccable.md:100-108\"]\n\n  Line 159:       \"scope\": \"motion\",\n\n  Line 160:       \"title\": \"do-not-add: AnimatePresence depth; reduced-motion/perf; standalone overdrive ref; 12-principles re-distill\",\n\n  Line 164:       \"why\": \"animate_presence_patterns + performance_reduced_motion already distill those thoroughly; overdrive is nice-to-have with high slop-risk; 12-principles already in motion_strategy + micro_interactions.\",\n\n  Line 165:       \"sources\": [\"design-motion/references/animate_presence_patterns.md\", \"design-motion/references/performance_reduced_motion.md\", \"001-corpus-research/research/gap-analysis.md:30\"]\n\n  Line 174:       \"why\": \"accessibility_performance already covers names/keyboard/focus/contrast/CWV(INP)/motion-perf; repair is sk-code's boundary (keep remediation detection-only); critique_hardening already covers Nielsen/persona/cognitive load.\",\n\n  Line 180:       \"title\": \"do-not-add: forward-authoring/DESIGN.md-from-directives; more gold examples; color/type/motion guidance; taste content\",\n\n  Line 184:       \"why\": \"Forward-authoring inverts the measured-extraction identity and was routed to an unbuilt design-spec child (net-new, out of scope, contradicts cardinal fidelity); 4 examples already span the format space; build/taste guidance belongs to foundations/motion/interface.\",\n\n  Line 191:     {\"approach\": \"standalone overdrive maximalist motion reference\", \"reason\": \"nice-to-have, high slop-risk, low everyday leverage\", \"evidence\": \"gap-analysis.md:30\"}\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research/research/lineages/opus48-claude2/deep-research-findings-registry.json:\n  Line 25:     {\"id\": \"F20\", \"label\": \"Corpus has two orthogonal axes: domain (interface/layout/color/motion) x mode (build/audit/refine)\", \"iteration\": 5},\n\n  Line 26:     {\"id\": \"F23\", \"label\": \"audit.md proves impeccable is a shared-context HUB with in-hub routing\", \"iteration\": 6},\n\n  Line 38:     \"taxonomy\": [\"sk-design-interface\", \"sk-design-foundations\", \"sk-design-motion\", \"sk-design-audit\", \"sk-design-spec\"],\n\n  Line 49:     {\"approach\": \"Standalone motion-performance child; pure mode-slicing\", \"iteration\": 5},\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion/research/.smoke-archive/lineages/gpt55fast/deep-research-findings-registry.json:\n  Line 13:       \"answer\": \"Audit and interface receive the densest asset additions; md-generator receives authoring template additions; foundations and motion receive targeted reference/top-up cards.\",\n\n  Line 40:       \"id\": \"F4-motion-advanced-bridge\",\n\n  Line 41:       \"mode\": \"design-motion\",\n\n  Line 44:       \"sources\": [\"design-motion/SKILL.md:81-95\", \"animate.md:108-158\", \"overdrive.md:19-31\"]\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research/research/lineages/mimo25pro/findings-registry.json:\n  Line 30:       \"label\": \"6 sub-skills proposed: visual, color, motion, layout, a11y, interaction\",\n\n  Line 68:     \"Parent routing precision (keyword vs intent classifier)\",\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/001-corpus-research/research/lineages/kimi27/deep-research-findings-registry.json:\n  Line 18:       \"statement\": \"The optimal sk-design taxonomy is 6 children: direction, foundations, motion, critique, system, presentation.\",\n\n  Line 44:       \"approach\": \"Split motion into multiple top-level children\",\n\n\n(Results truncated. Consider using a more specific path or pattern.)","metadata":{"matches":100,"truncated":true},"title":"motion|Mode A|routing|100","time":{"start":1782532355078,"end":1782532355091}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_04608b9a2db6066f016a3f4902f47881919784afa01e9cf350"}},"id":"prt_f073533fd001EOMyJ8015IGSVZ","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","messageID":"msg_f0734fc7c001CBtURNdH20g6fJ"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532355095,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_kseACOIqY7ecN8CEjK0bJBr9","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion/research/research.md","offset":1,"limit":420},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion/research/research.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Deep-Research Synthesis: sk-design reference and asset expansion\n2: \n3: > **Packet:** `154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion`\n4: > **Run:** 2-lineage fan-out, 16 iterations total (opus48-claude2 converged at 6, gpt55fast ran the full 10), merged into this consolidated matrix.\n5: > **Question:** Per sk-design sub-skill, what are the highest-leverage expansions to `references/` and `assets/`, grounded in the prior corpus research + gap-analysis and the 43-entry external corpus, honoring an \"if effective\" bar.\n6: > **Status:** Findings only. Every addition is a scope decision; implementation is a separate, gated follow-up. Out of scope: taxonomy/architecture, net-new sub-skills, implementation.\n7: \n8: The `Src` column records lineage agreement: **both** = both lineages independently proposed it (high confidence), **opus** / **gpt** = surfaced by one lineage.\n9: \n10: ---\n11: \n12: ## 1. Summary\n13: \n14: 1. **Both lineages independently ranked the same #1: a shared Brand-vs-Product operating register (`shared/register.md`).** Opus grounded it in `impeccable` + `bolder`/`quieter`/`distill`; GPT grounded it in `colorize` + `animate`. Independent convergence on the same must-add (gap 05) makes this the highest-confidence finding in the run.\n15: 2. **Four of five modes ship zero assets** (only md-generator has any). The highest-ROI first asset per mode is named below; the audit report template is the strongest case because the audit deliverable *is* a report.\n16: 3. **`design-audit` is the densest expansion target; `design-md-generator` is the leanest** (mostly do-NOT). Both lineages agree.\n17: 4. **The expansion is operational, not bulk import.** Both lineages explicitly reject importing the corpus wholesale; the leverage is in checklists, decision cards, and the register, not more style presets.\n18: 5. **One genuine divergence — md-generator forward-authoring — reconciles:** document the measured-vs-authored *boundary* (GPT's `authoring_boundary.md`) without building the forward-authoring *capability* (Opus routes that to the out-of-scope `design-spec` child). Both agree fidelity must not weaken.\n19: \n20: ---\n21: \n22: ## 2. Method\n23: \n24: Two heterogeneous lineages over the same charter, fresh context per iteration, one mode-focus per pass:\n25: - **opus48-claude2** (Claude Opus 4.8, cli-claude-code, xhigh): 6 iterations, converged (newInfoRatio 1.0 → 0.25; all key questions answered; quality guards passed). Produced the rigorous spine: cross-cutting prerequisites, priority ranking, negative-knowledge table.\n26: - **gpt55fast** (openai/gpt-5.5-fast, cli-opencode, xhigh): 10 iterations, final newInfoRatio 0.03. Produced more granular per-mode assets (motion cards, audit evidence references, foundations adaptation matrix).\n27: \n28: Grounding inputs (read-only): `001-corpus-research/research/research.md` (settled taxonomy + per-child corpus map), `001-corpus-research/research/gap-analysis.md` (current-state-validated severity table), the 43-entry `external/` corpus, and the live `sk-design/` tree.\n29: \n30: **Inventory baseline (filesystem-confirmed):**\n31: \n32: | Mode | references | assets | Maturity |\n33: |---|---|---|---|\n34: | design-interface | 13 | **0** | Vendored Anthropic base; no `corpus_map.md`; draws on none of the taste corpus |\n35: | design-foundations | 5 | **0** | Well-covered static system; real holes in data-viz + adaptation |\n36: | design-motion | 5 | **0** | Well-covered; gesture basics present; missing restraint gate + reusable cards |\n37: | design-audit | 5 | **0** | Densest expansion target; deliverable is a report yet ships no template |\n38: | design-md-generator | 8 (+4 examples) | 2 | Most mature; mostly do-NOT |\n39: \n40: ---\n41: \n42: ## 3. Per-Mode Expansion Matrix (primary deliverable)\n43: \n44: Effort: **S** ≈ ≤0.5d · **M** ≈ 0.5–1.5d. Severity reflects the gap-analysis, re-validated against live state.\n45: \n46: ### 3.1 Shared base (cross-cutting prerequisite)\n47: \n48: | ID | Type | Title | Why it raises usefulness | Sources | Src | Sev | Effort |\n49: |----|------|-------|--------------------------|---------|-----|-----|--------|\n50: | XC-1 | reference | `shared/register.md` — Brand-vs-Product operating register | The must-add prerequisite (gap 05). Gates density, motion budget, color dosage, copy register, anti-slop strictness, and audit severity. Absent today. Unblocks the most downstream work. | impeccable; bolder/quieter/distill; colorize:14; animate:14 | **both** | must (05) | M |\n51: | XC-2 | asset | `shared/assets/register_card.md` — one-page Brand/Product routing card | Operationalizes XC-1 with the Brand/Product questions + downstream defaults per mode. | anti_slop_principles; register sources above | gpt | should | S |\n52: \n53: **Do-NOT (shared):** a sixth \"intake/register\" child (register is shared content, not a sub-skill); duplicating N1/N2 independently in interface + audit (author once, reference twice); re-litigating gap severities.\n54: \n55: ### 3.2 design-interface\n56: \n57: Gaps: vendored base draws on none of the taste/craft corpus; zero assets; no mechanical layout pre-flight gate (N2); no mock-content discipline (N1).\n58: \n59: | ID | Type | Title | Why | Sources | Src | Sev | Effort |\n60: |----|------|-------|-----|---------|-----|-----|--------|\n61: | IF-A1 | asset | `assets/interface_preflight_card.md` — fill-in mechanical pass/fail card | Converts the prose two-pass into a checkable gate: hero line count, eyebrow/meta-label sweep, gapless bento, real-imagery, button contrast, copy audit, motion motivation, reduced-motion, mobile collapse, AI tells. First asset for the mode. | taste-skill:919; gpt-tasteskill:67; impeccable | **both** | should (N2) | M |\n62: | IF-R1 | reference | `references/design-process/brief_to_dials.md` — Design Read + three dials | Structured intake mapping variance/motion/density dials to layout/motion/density choices, with use-case presets. | taste-skill:43 | **both** | should (08t) | S–M |\n63: | IF-R2 | reference | `references/design-process/mechanical_defaults.md` | The mechanical anti-default checklist the aesthetic calibration omits. **Shared N2 artifact with audit AU-R5 (author once).** | gpt-tasteskill §2–7; redesign; taste §14 | opus | should (09/N2) | M |\n64: | IF-R3 | reference | `references/design-process/copy_and_mock_data.md` | Build-side N1: plausible names/numbers/copy, no lorem, no AI-tell phrasing, one-copy-register, image-seed discipline. Twin of audit AU-R4. | taste-skill:321; redesign; gpt-tasteskill §7 | **both** | should (N1) | S |\n65: | IF-R4 | reference | `references/design-process/visual_asset_strategy.md` | When to require real images vs generated imagery vs Simple Icons/devicon logos, with explicit placeholder slots. | taste-skill:262 | gpt | nice | S |\n66: | IF-R5 | subsection | AIDA + gapless-bento note (under `variation_diversity.md`) | Landing-page-only structure/bento math, explicitly NOT default for product UI. | gpt-tasteskill:22,42 | gpt | nice | S |\n67: \n68: **Do-NOT:** more aesthetic preset files as the first expansion (already guarded critique-against-only); gpt-taste Python-RNG randomization as a mandate (redundant with `variation_diversity.md`); GSAP-first / static-forbidden as default behavior (landing-page-only); forward DESIGN.md authoring.\n69: \n70: ### 3.3 design-foundations\n71: \n72: Gaps: no data-viz foundations; no adaptation matrix; no structured intake; zero assets. Gestalt/grid + OKLCH already covered (do-NOT line).\n73: \n74: | ID | Type | Title | Why | Sources | Src | Sev | Effort |\n75: |----|------|-------|-----|---------|-----|-----|--------|\n76: | FN-R1 | reference | `references/data_viz.md` — data-visualization foundations | The clearest coverage hole: chart-type selection, axis/encoding, color-for-data (sequential/diverging/categorical), sparklines, table alignment beyond tabular-nums. | colorize:85; designer-skills ui-design; gap 14d | **both** | should (14d) | M |\n77: | FN-R2 | reference | `references/layout/adaptation_matrix.md` | Device/input/context adaptation (mobile/tablet/desktop/print/constrained) as rethinking-for-context, not pixel scaling. | adapt:37 | gpt | should | S–M |\n78: | FN-R3 | reference | `references/intake/design_read_dials.md` — density-dial intake | Foundations owns the density dial of the shared three-dial intake. **Coordinate ownership with interface (see Open Questions).** | taste-skill §0–1 | opus | should (08t) | S |\n79: | FN-R4 | subsection | brand-seed color fold-in to `color/palette_theming.md` | Greenfield path: derive a palette from one brand seed when no system exists (gap N3). Keep small, no standalone file. | impeccable; gap N3 | **both** | nice (N3) | S |\n80: | FN-A1 | asset | `assets/token_starter.md` — fill-in OKLCH ramp + type + spacing scaffold | First foundations asset; wires the static-system refs into a fill-in keyed to `design_token_vocabulary.md`. (GPT's `density_structure_matrix.md` folds in here.) | oklch-skill; layout:61,150 | **both** | nice | M |\n81: \n82: **Do-NOT:** another OKLCH/contrast/dark-mode basics guide (already owned); splitting foundations into color/layout children (taxonomy); a heavy new Gestalt/grid reference (covered by `shared/cognitive_laws.md` + `layout_responsive.md`); taste-skill brief→design-system framework map (interface/sk-code concern).\n83: \n84: ### 3.4 design-motion\n85: \n86: Gaps: gesture basics already covered, but the restraint gate is missing; emil advanced-craft not distilled; no reusable pattern/failure cards; zero assets.\n87: \n88: | ID | Type | Title | Why | Sources | Src | Sev | Effort |\n89: |----|------|-------|-----|---------|-----|-----|--------|\n90: | MO-R1 | reference | `references/animation_decision_framework.md` — restraint gate | Strongest anti-slop motion lever: 100+/day = never animate, never animate keyboard-initiated actions, tens/day = reduce. Missing today. | emil-design-eng §1–2 | opus | should (08e) | S–M |\n91: | MO-A1 | asset | `assets/motion_pattern_cards.md` — reusable pattern cards | Loading/feedback/state/page-transition/gesture/toast/drag-drop/hover/focus cards with owner + state fields. First motion asset. | interaction-design:10 | gpt | should | S–M |\n92: | MO-A2 | asset | `assets/animate_presence_checklist.md` | Exit wrapper, exit prop, key, symmetry, presence hook, safeToRemove, mode, nested-exit checks. | mastering-animate-presence:21 | gpt | should | S |\n93: | MO-A3 | asset | `assets/motion_performance_failure_card.md` | Failure-mode card: layout thrash, scroll polling, endless rAF, mixed systems, layer promotion, paint-heavy effects, blur. | fixing-motion-performance:52 | gpt | should | S |\n94: | MO-R2 | subsection | advanced-craft + `polish_details` top-up to `micro_interactions.md` | popover transform-origin-from-trigger, `:active` scale(0.97), `scale(0.95)+opacity`, concentric radii, optical alignment, tabular nums. | emil-design-eng; make-interfaces-feel-better:19 | **both** | should (08e) | S |\n95: | MO-R3 | reference | `references/advanced_rendering.md` — propose-first toolkit | View Transitions morph-from-trigger, virtual scroll, GPU/Canvas for data, spring drag-drop — bounded by overdrive's propose-before-building. | overdrive; emil | opus | nice (06) | M |\n96: \n97: **Do-NOT:** gesture *basics* (already in `micro_interactions.md` §4); GSAP scroll paradigms as default mandates (admit only inside MO-R3); motion-performance *review* (audit's surface); a default \"all interfaces must be motion-rich\" rule; emil's \"Initial Response\" identity framing; a separate `design-interaction` child.\n98: \n99: ### 3.5 design-audit (densest)\n100: \n101: Gaps: no AI-fingerprint/model-tell catalog; no evidence-capture model; no remediation/transform routing; no a11y/hardening quick-fix surface; no report template despite the deliverable being a report.\n102: \n103: | ID | Type | Title | Why | Sources | Src | Sev | Effort |\n104: |----|------|-------|-----|---------|-----|-----|--------|\n105: | AU-R1 | reference | `references/ai_fingerprint_tells.md` — model-specific defect catalog | Highest-leverage single addition family-wide: concrete checkable Codex (tracking/ghost-card/over-round/sketchy-SVG/stripes), Gemini (img-hover), 2026-general (cream-bg/eyebrow-every-section/section-fade) tells. Turns \"feels AI-made\" into P0–P3 findings. | impeccable | opus | should (07) | M |\n106: | AU-A1 | asset | `assets/audit_report_template.md` — fill-in 5-dim `/20` + P0–P3 report | The strongest first-asset case in the family: the audit deliverable IS a report. Findings-first skeleton with score, anti-pattern verdict, owner mapping, evidence caveats. | audit:12; audit_contract | **both** | should | M |\n107: | AU-R2 | reference | `references/transform_remediation.md` — bolder/quieter/distill verbs (register-gated) | Maps directional transform verbs + redesign to findings, owner mode, accepted remediation path. **Depends on XC-1.** Shared with interface. | bolder; quieter; distill; redesign; gap 04/11 | **both** | should (04/11) | S–M |\n108: | AU-R3 | reference | `references/evidence_capture.md` | Evidence model: file/source resolution, browser evidence, deterministic scans, screenshot/overlay notes, fallback labels. | critique:12 | gpt | should | M |\n109: | AU-A2 | asset | `assets/a11y_quick_fixes.md` | Snippet-level fixes: accessible names, keyboard, focus/dialogs, semantics, forms/errors, announcements, contrast, motion. | fixing-accessibility:33 | gpt | should | S |\n110: | AU-R4 | reference | `references/hardening_edge_cases.md` | Production-readiness matrix: extreme inputs, API/network errors, permissions, rate limits, concurrency, i18n/RTL, text expansion, CJK/emoji. | harden:14 | gpt | should | S–M |\n111: | AU-R5 | reference | mock-content review check + mechanical layout gate (folded into `anti_patterns_production.md`) | Review-side N1 + N2 twins of interface IF-R3/IF-R2. Author the gates once, audit references the review view. | redesign; taste §14; impeccable | opus | should (N1/N2) | S |\n112: \n113: **Do-NOT:** critique/cognitive-load/Nielsen/hardening/polish duplication (already in `critique_hardening.md`); CWV/a11y/perf duplication (already in `accessibility_performance.md`; do not revert INP→FID); implementing fixes (sk-code's boundary); full two-sub-agent critique orchestration (keep evidence principles only); elevating a11y to a standalone child.\n114: \n115: ### 3.6 design-md-generator (leanest — expansion mostly not effective)\n116: \n117: Gaps: essentially none. The only skew: all 4 worked examples are SaaS-minimalist. The one genuine in-scope reference is the authoring boundary (the divergence, reconciled).\n118: \n119: | ID | Type | Title | Why | Sources | Src | Sev | Effort |\n120: |----|------|-------|-----|---------|-----|-----|--------|\n121: | MD-R1 | reference | `references/authoring_boundary.md` — measured vs brief-authored vs inferred | Clarifies the fidelity boundary + source-of-truth labels WITHOUT building forward-authoring. Protects the cardinal fidelity rule against the design-spec pull. | md SKILL cardinal rule:248; stitch-skill:17 (boundary only) | gpt | should | S–M |\n122: | MD-A1 | asset | `assets/source_of_truth_router_card.md` | Quick card: measured tokens / brief-provided / inferred / missing-backing? Prevents fabricated values. | design_md_format cardinal rules:27 | gpt | nice | S |\n123: | MD-A2 | asset (example) | 5th DESIGN.md exemplar in a non-SaaS aesthetic (editorial / e-commerce / maximalist) | All 4 exemplars are SaaS-minimalist; one distinct aesthetic broadens format coverage. Requires a real extraction run, so only nice-to-have. | v3 format + fresh extraction | **both** | nice | S–M |\n124: \n125: **Do-NOT (dominant verdict):** forward DESIGN.md/PRODUCT.md *authoring capability* (stitch, gap 10 — different input contract; routes to the net-new `design-spec` child; out of scope for 009); a second extraction backend/crawler (pipeline already extracts/writes/validates/reports); duplicate format/taxonomy references; inventing values or weakening `tokens.json` fidelity.\n126: \n127: ---\n128: \n129: ## 4. Family-Wide Priority Ranking\n130: \n131: Should-adds by leverage (corpus strength × coverage hole × checkability × cross-lineage agreement):\n132: \n133: 1. **XC-1 `shared/register.md`** (must) — both lineages' #1; gates the most downstream work.\n134: 2. **IF-A1 + AU-A1 first assets** (both) — the two highest-ROI fill-in cards (preflight + audit report).\n135: 3. **AU-R1 model-tell catalog** (opus) — most concrete, highest checkable value, no current analog.\n136: 4. **N1/N2 author-once gates** (IF-R2 + IF-R3 + AU-R5, both) — convert the most common LLM defects into checkable gates.\n137: 5. **AU-R2 transform/remediation verbs** (both, register-dependent) + **AU-R3 evidence-capture** (gpt).\n138: 6. **FN-R1 data-viz** (both) + **FN-R2 adaptation matrix** (gpt) — the two real foundations holes.\n139: 7. **MO-R1 restraint gate** (opus) + the three motion asset cards MO-A1/A2/A3 (gpt).\n140: 8. **MD-R1 authoring-boundary** (gpt) — low effort, protects fidelity.\n141: \n142: Nice-to-haves (IF-R4/R5, FN-R4/A1, MO-R2/R3, AU-R5 enrich, MD-A1/A2) rank below.\n143: \n144: ---\n145: \n146: ## 5. Recommended Implementation Sequence (gated follow-up)\n147: \n148: 1. **XC-1 `shared/register.md` + XC-2 card first** — unblocks AU-R1/R2 + IF-R1/R2.\n149: 2. **Interface + audit first-assets** (IF-A1, AU-A1) — highest operator leverage; converts the taste corpus into repeatable checks.\n150: 3. **Author N1 + N2 once** (interface owns, audit references) — prevents drift.\n151: 4. **Audit cluster** (AU-R1, AU-R2, AU-R3, AU-A2) — densest payoff, most concrete corpus.\n152: 5. **Foundations holes** (FN-R1 data-viz, FN-R2 adaptation) — without duplicating basics.\n153: 6. **Motion cards** (MO-R1 gate + MO-A1/A2/A3) — package known rules into reusable cards.\n154: 7. **md-generator authoring-boundary** (MD-R1) — adds the boundary while protecting cardinal fidelity. Treat md-generator as otherwise done.\n155: \n156: ---\n157: \n158: ## 6. Eliminated Alternatives (negative knowledge)\n159: \n160: | Approach | Reason eliminated | Src |\n161: |---|---|---|\n162: | Bulk-import the external corpus | Leverage is operational refs + cards, not volume; both lineages reject it | both |\n163: | gpt-taste Python-RNG \"true randomization\" as an interface mandate | Redundant with `variation_diversity.md`; contradicts grounding-first | opus |\n164: | Aesthetic presets as a chooser in interface | Already guarded critique-against-only; must not become pick-a-vibe | both |\n165: | Splitting foundations into color/layout children | Taxonomy, decided | both |\n166: | Heavy new Gestalt/grid reference | Already covered by `shared/cognitive_laws.md` + `layout_responsive.md` | opus |\n167: | Adding gesture basics to motion | Already in `micro_interactions.md` §4 | opus |\n168: | Folding motion-performance *review* into motion | Owned by audit; build-vs-review boundary is correct | both |\n169: | Overdrive/advanced rendering as core motion behavior | Nice-to-have only; propose-first, not default | both |\n170: | Duplicating critique/CWV/a11y in new audit references | Already deep in `critique_hardening.md` + `accessibility_performance.md` | both |\n171: | Implementing fixes inside audit | Audit reports/scores; implementation is sk-code | both |\n172: | Forward DESIGN.md authoring *capability* in md-generator | Different input contract; routes to net-new `design-spec`; out of scope (boundary doc IS in scope) | both |\n173: | A second extraction backend in md-generator | Pipeline already extracts/writes/validates/reports | gpt |\n174: | `designer-skills-main` full process lifecycle, slides/canvas/poster, output-skill | Out-of-family / scope rulings in gap-analysis | gpt |\n175: | A sixth intake/register child | Register is shared content, not a sub-skill | opus |\n176: \n177: ---\n178: \n179: ## 7. Open Questions / Divergences\n180: \n181: 1. **md-generator forward-authoring (the one real divergence).** Opus routes forward-authoring fully out of scope (to a net-new `design-spec` child); GPT proposes an `authoring_boundary.md` reference + source-of-truth router. **Reconciliation:** the boundary *documentation* (labels for measured / brief-provided / inferred / absent) is in-scope and low-risk; the forward-authoring *capability* stays out of scope. Both agree fidelity must not weaken.\n182: 2. **Three-dials ownership.** `VISUAL_DENSITY`→foundations, `DESIGN_VARIANCE`→interface, `MOTION_INTENSITY`→motion. gap-analysis routes the intake to foundations; an interface/shared home may fit better. Decide at build time (affects IF-R1 vs FN-R3).\n183: 3. **N1/N2 owning home.** `shared/` vs interface-owned-with-audit-reference. Either preserves \"author once\"; pick at build time.\n184: 4. **Effort estimates are coarse (S/M).** Calibrate against actual authoring + validation in the follow-up.\n185: 5. **Pre-existing defect to fix alongside:** `design-audit/SKILL.md §8` cites `changelog/v1.0.0.1.md`, which the v1.0.0.0 pre-release collapse removed. Repoint to `v1.0.0.0.md`.\n186: \n187: ---\n188: \n189: <!-- ANCHOR:references -->\n190: ## 8. References\n191: \n192: ### This run (lineage artifacts)\n193: - `research/lineages/opus48-claude2/research.md` + `iterations/iteration-00{1..6}.md` (converged)\n194: - `research/lineages/gpt55fast/research.md` + `iterations/iteration-0{01..10}.md`\n195: - `research/deep-research-findings-registry.json` (merged, 18 key findings) + `research/fanout-attribution.md`\n196: \n197: ### Grounding inputs (read-only)\n198: - `001-corpus-research/research/research.md` (settled taxonomy + per-child corpus map)\n199: - `001-corpus-research/research/gap-analysis.md` (current-state-validated severity table)\n200: - `154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion/spec.md`\n201: \n202: ### Corpus sources cited (subset of the 43-entry external/)\n203: - Interface/craft: `gpt-tasteskill`, `taste-skill`, `redesign-skill`, `bencium-innovative-ux-designer`, `design-lab`\n204: - Foundations: `oklch-skill`, `layout`, `baseline`, `adapt`, `colorize`, `designer-skills-main` (ui-design data-viz)\n205: - Motion: `emil-design-eng`, `overdrive`, `animate`, `interaction-design`, `mastering-animate-presence`, `fixing-motion-performance`, `make-interfaces-feel-better`\n206: - Audit/transform: `impeccable`, `redesign-skill`, `bolder`, `quieter`, `distill`, `audit`, `critique`, `polish`, `harden`, `fixing-accessibility`\n207: - Spec/authoring: `stitch-skill` (boundary only; forward-authoring routed out of scope)\n208: <!-- /ANCHOR:references -->\n\n(End of file - total 208 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Deep-Research Synthesis: sk-design reference and asset expansion\n\n> **Packet:** `154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion`\n> **Run:** 2-lineage fan-out, 16 iterations total (opus48-claude2 converged at 6, gpt55fast ran the full 10), merged into this consolidated matrix.\n> **Question:** Per sk-design sub-skill, what are the highest-leverage expansions to `references/` and `assets/`, grounded in the prior corpus research + gap-analysis and the 43-entry external corpus, honoring an \"if effective\" bar.\n> **Status:** Findings only. Every addition is a scope decision; implementation is a separate, gated follow-up. Out of scope: taxonomy/architecture, net-new sub-skills, implementation.\n\nThe `Src` column records lineage agreement: **both** = both lineages independently proposed it (high confidence), **opus** / **gpt** = surfaced by one lineage.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Summary\n\n1. **Both lineages independently ranked the same #1: a shared Brand-vs-Product operating register (`shared/register.md`).** Opus grounded it in `impeccable` + `bolder`/`quieter`/`distill`; GPT grounded it in `colorize` + `animate`. Independent convergence on the same must-add (gap 05) makes this the highest-confidence finding in the run.\n2. **Four of five modes ship zero assets** (only md-generator has any). The highest-ROI first asset per mode is named below; the audit report template is the strongest case because the audit deliverable *is* a report.\n3. **`design-audit` is the densest expansion target; `design-md-generator` is the leanest** (mostly do-NOT). Both lineages agree.\n4. **The expansion is operational, not bulk import.** Both lineages explicitly reject importing the corpus wholesale; the leverage is in checklists, decision cards, and the register, not more style presets.\n5. **One genuine divergence — md-generator forward-authoring — reconciles:** document the measured-vs-authored *boundary* (GPT's `authoring_boundary.md`) without building the forward-authoring *capability* (Opus routes that to the out-of-scope `design-spec` child). Both agree fidelity must not weaken.\n\n---","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion/research/research.md","text":"# Deep-Research Synthesis: sk-design reference and asset expansion\n\n> **Packet:** `154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion`\n> **Run:** 2-lineage fan-out, 16 iterations total (opus48-claude2 converged at 6, gpt55fast ran the full 10), merged into this consolidated matrix.\n> **Question:** Per sk-design sub-skill, what are the highest-leverage expansions to `references/` and `assets/`, grounded in the prior corpus research + gap-analysis and the 43-entry external corpus, honoring an \"if effective\" bar.\n> **Status:** Findings only. Every addition is a scope decision; implementation is a separate, gated follow-up. Out of scope: taxonomy/architecture, net-new sub-skills, implementation.\n\nThe `Src` column records lineage agreement: **both** = both lineages independently proposed it (high confidence), **opus** / **gpt** = surfaced by one lineage.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Summary\n\n1. **Both lineages independently ranked the same #1: a shared Brand-vs-Product operating register (`shared/register.md`).** Opus grounded it in `impeccable` + `bolder`/`quieter`/`distill`; GPT grounded it in `colorize` + `animate`. Independent convergence on the same must-add (gap 05) makes this the highest-confidence finding in the run.\n2. **Four of five modes ship zero assets** (only md-generator has any). The highest-ROI first asset per mode is named below; the audit report template is the strongest case because the audit deliverable *is* a report.\n3. **`design-audit` is the densest expansion target; `design-md-generator` is the leanest** (mostly do-NOT). Both lineages agree.\n4. **The expansion is operational, not bulk import.** Both lineages explicitly reject importing the corpus wholesale; the leverage is in checklists, decision cards, and the register, not more style presets.\n5. **One genuine divergence — md-generator forward-authoring — reconciles:** document the measured-vs-authored *boundary* (GPT's `authoring_boundary.md`) without building the forward-authoring *capability* (Opus routes that to the out-of-scope `design-spec` child). Both agree fidelity must not weaken.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Method\n\nTwo heterogeneous lineages over the same charter, fresh context per iteration, one mode-focus per pass:\n- **opus48-claude2** (Claude Opus 4.8, cli-claude-code, xhigh): 6 iterations, converged (newInfoRatio 1.0 → 0.25; all key questions answered; quality guards passed). Produced the rigorous spine: cross-cutting prerequisites, priority ranking, negative-knowledge table.\n- **gpt55fast** (openai/gpt-5.5-fast, cli-opencode, xhigh): 10 iterations, final newInfoRatio 0.03. Produced more granular per-mode assets (motion cards, audit evidence references, foundations adaptation matrix).\n\nGrounding inputs (read-only): `001-corpus-research/research/research.md` (settled taxonomy + per-child corpus map), `001-corpus-research/research/gap-analysis.md` (current-state-validated severity table), the 43-entry `external/` corpus, and the live `sk-design/` tree.\n\n**Inventory baseline (filesystem-confirmed):**\n\n| Mode | references | assets | Maturity |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| design-interface | 13 | **0** | Vendored Anthropic base; no `corpus_map.md`; draws on none of the taste corpus |\n| design-foundations | 5 | **0** | Well-covered static system; real holes in data-viz + adaptation |\n| design-motion | 5 | **0** | Well-covered; gesture basics present; missing restraint gate + reusable cards |\n| design-audit | 5 | **0** | Densest expansion target; deliverable is a report yet ships no template |\n| design-md-generator | 8 (+4 examples) | 2 | Most mature; mostly do-NOT |\n\n---\n\n## 3. Per-Mode Expansion Matrix (primary deliverable)\n\nEffort: **S** ≈ ≤0.5d · **M** ≈ 0.5–1.5d. Severity reflects the gap-analysis, re-validated against live state.\n\n### 3.1 Shared base (cross-cutting prerequisite)\n\n| ID | Type | Title | Why it raises usefulness | Sources | Src | Sev | Effort |\n|----|------|-------|--------------------------|---------|-----|-----|--------|\n| XC-1 | reference | `shared/register.md` — Brand-vs-Product operating register | The must-add prerequisite (gap 05). Gates density, motion budget, color dosage, copy register, anti-slop strictness, and audit severity. Absent today. Unblocks the most downstream work. | impeccable; bolder/quieter/distill; colorize:14; animate:14 | **both** | must (05) | M |\n| XC-2 | asset | `shared/assets/register_card.md` — one-page Brand/Product routing card | Operationalizes XC-1 with the Brand/Product questions + downstream defaults per mode. | anti_slop_principles; register sources above | gpt | should | S |\n\n**Do-NOT (shared):** a sixth \"intake/register\" child (register is shared content, not a sub-skill); duplicating N1/N2 independently in interface + audit (author once, reference twice); re-litigating gap severities.\n\n### 3.2 design-interface\n\nGaps: vendored base draws on none of the taste/craft corpus; zero assets; no mechanical layout pre-flight gate (N2); no mock-content discipline (N1).\n\n| ID | Type | Title | Why | Sources | Src | Sev | Effort |\n|----|------|-------|-----|---------|-----|-----|--------|\n| IF-A1 | asset | `assets/interface_preflight_card.md` — fill-in mechanical pass/fail card | Converts the prose two-pass into a checkable gate: hero line count, eyebrow/meta-label sweep, gapless bento, real-imagery, button contrast, copy audit, motion motivation, reduced-motion, mobile collapse, AI tells. First asset for the mode. | taste-skill:919; gpt-tasteskill:67; impeccable | **both** | should (N2) | M |\n| IF-R1 | reference | `references/design-process/brief_to_dials.md` — Design Read + three dials | Structured intake mapping variance/motion/density dials to layout/motion/density choices, with use-case presets. | taste-skill:43 | **both** | should (08t) | S–M |\n| IF-R2 | reference | `references/design-process/mechanical_defaults.md` | The mechanical anti-default checklist the aesthetic calibration omits. **Shared N2 artifact with audit AU-R5 (author once).** | gpt-tasteskill §2–7; redesign; taste §14 | opus | should (09/N2) | M |\n| IF-R3 | reference | `references/design-process/copy_and_mock_data.md` | Build-side N1: plausible names/numbers/copy, no lorem, no AI-tell phrasing, one-copy-register, image-seed discipline. Twin of audit AU-R4. | taste-skill:321; redesign; gpt-tasteskill §7 | **both** | should (N1) | S |\n| IF-R4 | reference | `references/design-process/visual_asset_strategy.md` | When to require real images vs generated imagery vs Simple Icons/devicon logos, with explicit placeholder slots. | taste-skill:262 | gpt | nice | S |\n| IF-R5 | subsection | AIDA + gapless-bento note (under `variation_diversity.md`) | Landing-page-only structure/bento math, explicitly NOT default for product UI. | gpt-tasteskill:22,42 | gpt | nice | S |\n\n**Do-NOT:** more aesthetic preset files as the first expansion (already guarded critique-against-only); gpt-taste Python-RNG randomization as a mandate (redundant with `variation_diversity.md`); GSAP-first / static-forbidden as default behavior (landing-page-only); forward DESIGN.md authoring.\n\n### 3.3 design-foundations\n\nGaps: no data-viz foundations; no adaptation matrix; no structured intake; zero assets. Gestalt/grid + OKLCH already covered (do-NOT line).\n\n| ID | Type | Title | Why | Sources | Src | Sev | Effort |\n|----|------|-------|-----|---------|-----|-----|--------|\n| FN-R1 | reference | `references/data_viz.md` — data-visualization foundations | The clearest coverage hole: chart-type selection, axis/encoding, color-for-data (sequential/diverging/categorical), sparklines, table alignment beyond tabular-nums. | colorize:85; designer-skills ui-design; gap 14d | **both** | should (14d) | M |\n| FN-R2 | reference | `references/layout/adaptation_matrix.md` | Device/input/context adaptation (mobile/tablet/desktop/print/constrained) as rethinking-for-context, not pixel scaling. | adapt:37 | gpt | should | S–M |\n| FN-R3 | reference | `references/intake/design_read_dials.md` — density-dial intake | Foundations owns the density dial of the shared three-dial intake. **Coordinate ownership with interface (see Open Questions).** | taste-skill §0–1 | opus | should (08t) | S |\n| FN-R4 | subsection | brand-seed color fold-in to `color/palette_theming.md` | Greenfield path: derive a palette from one brand seed when no system exists (gap N3). Keep small, no standalone file. | impeccable; gap N3 | **both** | nice (N3) | S |\n| FN-A1 | asset | `assets/token_starter.md` — fill-in OKLCH ramp + type + spacing scaffold | First foundations asset; wires the static-system refs into a fill-in keyed to `design_token_vocabulary.md`. (GPT's `density_structure_matrix.md` folds in here.) | oklch-skill; layout:61,150 | **both** | nice | M |\n\n**Do-NOT:** another OKLCH/contrast/dark-mode basics guide (already owned); splitting foundations into color/layout children (taxonomy); a heavy new Gestalt/grid reference (covered by `shared/cognitive_laws.md` + `layout_responsive.md`); taste-skill brief→design-system framework map (interface/sk-code concern).\n\n### 3.4 design-motion\n\nGaps: gesture basics already covered, but the restraint gate is missing; emil advanced-craft not distilled; no reusable pattern/failure cards; zero assets.\n\n| ID | Type | Title | Why | Sources | Src | Sev | Effort |\n|----|------|-------|-----|---------|-----|-----|--------|\n| MO-R1 | reference | `references/animation_decision_framework.md` — restraint gate | Strongest anti-slop motion lever: 100+/day = never animate, never animate keyboard-initiated actions, tens/day = reduce. Missing today. | emil-design-eng §1–2 | opus | should (08e) | S–M |\n| MO-A1 | asset | `assets/motion_pattern_cards.md` — reusable pattern cards | Loading/feedback/state/page-transition/gesture/toast/drag-drop/hover/focus cards with owner + state fields. First motion asset. | interaction-design:10 | gpt | should | S–M |\n| MO-A2 | asset | `assets/animate_presence_checklist.md` | Exit wrapper, exit prop, key, symmetry, presence hook, safeToRemove, mode, nested-exit checks. | mastering-animate-presence:21 | gpt | should | S |\n| MO-A3 | asset | `assets/motion_performance_failure_card.md` | Failure-mode card: layout thrash, scroll polling, endless rAF, mixed systems, layer promotion, paint-heavy effects, blur. | fixing-motion-performance:52 | gpt | should | S |\n| MO-R2 | subsection | advanced-craft + `polish_details` top-up to `micro_interactions.md` | popover transform-origin-from-trigger, `:active` scale(0.97), `scale(0.95)+opacity`, concentric radii, optical alignment, tabular nums. | emil-design-eng; make-interfaces-feel-better:19 | **both** | should (08e) | S |\n| MO-R3 | reference | `references/advanced_rendering.md` — propose-first toolkit | View Transitions morph-from-trigger, virtual scroll, GPU/Canvas for data, spring drag-drop — bounded by overdrive's propose-before-building. | overdrive; emil | opus | nice (06) | M |\n\n**Do-NOT:** gesture *basics* (already in `micro_interactions.md` §4); GSAP scroll paradigms as default mandates (admit only inside MO-R3); motion-performance *review* (audit's surface); a default \"all interfaces must be motion-rich\" rule; emil's \"Initial Response\" identity framing; a separate `design-interaction` child.\n\n### 3.5 design-audit (densest)\n\nGaps: no AI-fingerprint/model-tell catalog; no evidence-capture model; no remediation/transform routing; no a11y/hardening quick-fix surface; no report template despite the deliverable being a report.\n\n| ID | Type | Title | Why | Sources | Src | Sev | Effort |\n|----|------|-------|-----|---------|-----|-----|--------|\n| AU-R1 | reference | `references/ai_fingerprint_tells.md` — model-specific defect catalog | Highest-leverage single addition family-wide: concrete checkable Codex (tracking/ghost-card/over-round/sketchy-SVG/stripes), Gemini (img-hover), 2026-general (cream-bg/eyebrow-every-section/section-fade) tells. Turns \"feels AI-made\" into P0–P3 findings. | impeccable | opus | should (07) | M |\n| AU-A1 | asset | `assets/audit_report_template.md` — fill-in 5-dim `/20` + P0–P3 report | The strongest first-asset case in the family: the audit deliverable IS a report. Findings-first skeleton with score, anti-pattern verdict, owner mapping, evidence caveats. | audit:12; audit_contract | **both** | should | M |\n| AU-R2 | reference | `references/transform_remediation.md` — bolder/quieter/distill verbs (register-gated) | Maps directional transform verbs + redesign to findings, owner mode, accepted remediation path. **Depends on XC-1.** Shared with interface. | bolder; quieter; distill; redesign; gap 04/11 | **both** | should (04/11) | S–M |\n| AU-R3 | reference | `references/evidence_capture.md` | Evidence model: file/source resolution, browser evidence, deterministic scans, screenshot/overlay notes, fallback labels. | critique:12 | gpt | should | M |\n| AU-A2 | asset | `assets/a11y_quick_fixes.md` | Snippet-level fixes: accessible names, keyboard, focus/dialogs, semantics, forms/errors, announcements, contrast, motion. | fixing-accessibility:33 | gpt | should | S |\n| AU-R4 | reference | `references/hardening_edge_cases.md` | Production-readiness matrix: extreme inputs, API/network errors, permissions, rate limits, concurrency, i18n/RTL, text expansion, CJK/emoji. | harden:14 | gpt | should | S–M |\n| AU-R5 | reference | mock-content review check + mechanical layout gate (folded into `anti_patterns_production.md`) | Review-side N1 + N2 twins of interface IF-R3/IF-R2. Author the gates once, audit references the review view. | redesign; taste §14; impeccable | opus | should (N1/N2) | S |\n\n**Do-NOT:** critique/cognitive-load/Nielsen/hardening/polish duplication (already in `critique_hardening.md`); CWV/a11y/perf duplication (already in `accessibility_performance.md`; do not revert INP→FID); implementing fixes (sk-code's boundary); full two-sub-agent critique orchestration (keep evidence principles only); elevating a11y to a standalone child.\n\n### 3.6 design-md-generator (leanest — expansion mostly not effective)\n\nGaps: essentially none. The only skew: all 4 worked examples are SaaS-minimalist. The one genuine in-scope reference is the authoring boundary (the divergence, reconciled).\n\n| ID | Type | Title | Why | Sources | Src | Sev | Effort |\n|----|------|-------|-----|---------|-----|-----|--------|\n| MD-R1 | reference | `references/authoring_boundary.md` — measured vs brief-authored vs inferred | Clarifies the fidelity boundary + source-of-truth labels WITHOUT building forward-authoring. Protects the cardinal fidelity rule against the design-spec pull. | md SKILL cardinal rule:248; stitch-skill:17 (boundary only) | gpt | should | S–M |\n| MD-A1 | asset | `assets/source_of_truth_router_card.md` | Quick card: measured tokens / brief-provided / inferred / missing-backing? Prevents fabricated values. | design_md_format cardinal rules:27 | gpt | nice | S |\n| MD-A2 | asset (example) | 5th DESIGN.md exemplar in a non-SaaS aesthetic (editorial / e-commerce / maximalist) | All 4 exemplars are SaaS-minimalist; one distinct aesthetic broadens format coverage. Requires a real extraction run, so only nice-to-have. | v3 format + fresh extraction | **both** | nice | S–M |\n\n**Do-NOT (dominant verdict):** forward DESIGN.md/PRODUCT.md *authoring capability* (stitch, gap 10 — different input contract; routes to the net-new `design-spec` child; out of scope for 009); a second extraction backend/crawler (pipeline already extracts/writes/validates/reports); duplicate format/taxonomy references; inventing values or weakening `tokens.json` fidelity.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Family-Wide Priority Ranking\n\nShould-adds by leverage (corpus strength × coverage hole × checkability × cross-lineage agreement):\n\n1. **XC-1 `shared/register.md`** (must) — both lineages' #1; gates the most downstream work.\n2. **IF-A1 + AU-A1 first assets** (both) — the two highest-ROI fill-in cards (preflight + audit report).\n3. **AU-R1 model-tell catalog** (opus) — most concrete, highest checkable value, no current analog.\n4. **N1/N2 author-once gates** (IF-R2 + IF-R3 + AU-R5, both) — convert the most common LLM defects into checkable gates.\n5. **AU-R2 transform/remediation verbs** (both, register-dependent) + **AU-R3 evidence-capture** (gpt).\n6. **FN-R1 data-viz** (both) + **FN-R2 adaptation matrix** (gpt) — the two real foundations holes.\n7. **MO-R1 restraint gate** (opus) + the three motion asset cards MO-A1/A2/A3 (gpt).\n8. **MD-R1 authoring-boundary** (gpt) — low effort, protects fidelity.\n\nNice-to-haves (IF-R4/R5, FN-R4/A1, MO-R2/R3, AU-R5 enrich, MD-A1/A2) rank below.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Recommended Implementation Sequence (gated follow-up)\n\n1. **XC-1 `shared/register.md` + XC-2 card first** — unblocks AU-R1/R2 + IF-R1/R2.\n2. **Interface + audit first-assets** (IF-A1, AU-A1) — highest operator leverage; converts the taste corpus into repeatable checks.\n3. **Author N1 + N2 once** (interface owns, audit references) — prevents drift.\n4. **Audit cluster** (AU-R1, AU-R2, AU-R3, AU-A2) — densest payoff, most concrete corpus.\n5. **Foundations holes** (FN-R1 data-viz, FN-R2 adaptation) — without duplicating basics.\n6. **Motion cards** (MO-R1 gate + MO-A1/A2/A3) — package known rules into reusable cards.\n7. **md-generator authoring-boundary** (MD-R1) — adds the boundary while protecting cardinal fidelity. Treat md-generator as otherwise done.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Eliminated Alternatives (negative knowledge)\n\n| Approach | Reason eliminated | Src |\n|---|---|---|\n| Bulk-import the external corpus | Leverage is operational refs + cards, not volume; both lineages reject it | both |\n| gpt-taste Python-RNG \"true randomization\" as an interface mandate | Redundant with `variation_diversity.md`; contradicts grounding-first | opus |\n| Aesthetic presets as a chooser in interface | Already guarded critique-against-only; must not become pick-a-vibe | both |\n| Splitting foundations into color/layout children | Taxonomy, decided | both |\n| Heavy new Gestalt/grid reference | Already covered by `shared/cognitive_laws.md` + `layout_responsive.md` | opus |\n| Adding gesture basics to motion | Already in `micro_interactions.md` §4 | opus |\n| Folding motion-performance *review* into motion | Owned by audit; build-vs-review boundary is correct | both |\n| Overdrive/advanced rendering as core motion behavior | Nice-to-have only; propose-first, not default | both |\n| Duplicating critique/CWV/a11y in new audit references | Already deep in `critique_hardening.md` + `accessibility_performance.md` | both |\n| Implementing fixes inside audit | Audit reports/scores; implementation is sk-code | both |\n| Forward DESIGN.md authoring *capability* in md-generator | Different input contract; routes to net-new `design-spec`; out of scope (boundary doc IS in scope) | both |\n| A second extraction backend in md-generator | Pipeline already extracts/writes/validates/reports | gpt |\n| `designer-skills-main` full process lifecycle, slides/canvas/poster, output-skill | Out-of-family / scope rulings in gap-analysis | gpt |\n| A sixth intake/register child | Register is shared content, not a sub-skill | opus |\n\n---\n\n## 7. Open Questions / Divergences\n\n1. **md-generator forward-authoring (the one real divergence).** Opus routes forward-authoring fully out of scope (to a net-new `design-spec` child); GPT proposes an `authoring_boundary.md` reference + source-of-truth router. **Reconciliation:** the boundary *documentation* (labels for measured / brief-provided / inferred / absent) is in-scope and low-risk; the forward-authoring *capability* stays out of scope. Both agree fidelity must not weaken.\n2. **Three-dials ownership.** `VISUAL_DENSITY`→foundations, `DESIGN_VARIANCE`→interface, `MOTION_INTENSITY`→motion. gap-analysis routes the intake to foundations; an interface/shared home may fit better. Decide at build time (affects IF-R1 vs FN-R3).\n3. **N1/N2 owning home.** `shared/` vs interface-owned-with-audit-reference. Either preserves \"author once\"; pick at build time.\n4. **Effort estimates are coarse (S/M).** Calibrate against actual authoring + validation in the follow-up.\n5. **Pre-existing defect to fix alongside:** `design-audit/SKILL.md §8` cites `changelog/v1.0.0.1.md`, which the v1.0.0.0 pre-release collapse removed. Repoint to `v1.0.0.0.md`.\n\n---\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:references -->\n## 8. References\n\n### This run (lineage artifacts)\n- `research/lineages/opus48-claude2/research.md` + `iterations/iteration-00{1..6}.md` (converged)\n- `research/lineages/gpt55fast/research.md` + `iterations/iteration-0{01..10}.md`\n- `research/deep-research-findings-registry.json` (merged, 18 key findings) + `research/fanout-attribution.md`\n\n### Grounding inputs (read-only)\n- `001-corpus-research/research/research.md` (settled taxonomy + per-child corpus map)\n- `001-corpus-research/research/gap-analysis.md` (current-state-validated severity table)\n- `154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion/spec.md`\n\n### Corpus sources cited (subset of the 43-entry external/)\n- Interface/craft: `gpt-tasteskill`, `taste-skill`, `redesign-skill`, `bencium-innovative-ux-designer`, `design-lab`\n- Foundations: `oklch-skill`, `layout`, `baseline`, `adapt`, `colorize`, `designer-skills-main` (ui-design data-viz)\n- Motion: `emil-design-eng`, `overdrive`, `animate`, `interaction-design`, `mastering-animate-presence`, `fixing-motion-performance`, `make-interfaces-feel-better`\n- Audit/transform: `impeccable`, `redesign-skill`, `bolder`, `quieter`, `distill`, `audit`, `critique`, `polish`, `harden`, `fixing-accessibility`\n- Spec/authoring: `stitch-skill` (boundary only; forward-authoring routed out of scope)\n<!-- /ANCHOR:references -->","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":208,"totalLines":208,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/009-reference-asset-expansion/research/research.md","time":{"start":1782532355080,"end":1782532355093}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_04608b9a2db6066f016a3f4902f480819187ddd36940923b28"}},"id":"prt_f0735340700135j7WAWSy8wdC3","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","messageID":"msg_f0734fc7c001CBtURNdH20g6fJ"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1782532355404,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","part":{"id":"prt_f0735354a001K95B1eDwmjTwQ9","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"ab87b191cf288cd2cf6e378b1a7cd773ba95a6e3","messageID":"msg_f0734fc7c001CBtURNdH20g6fJ","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":84031,"input":5876,"output":272,"reasoning":59,"cache":{"write":0,"read":77824}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1782532357408,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","part":{"id":"prt_f07353d1e001Z9BZfN9vkmCNTT","messageID":"msg_f0735367b001G1KCl9Imxmz1VM","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","snapshot":"ab87b191cf288cd2cf6e378b1a7cd773ba95a6e3","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532370808,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_V9fvY5QbmC0cJUAJyK3BQKYI","state":{"status":"error","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/references","offset":1,"limit":50},"error":"File not found: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/references","time":{"start":1782532370805,"end":1782532370807}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0b414214e37777ed016a3f4912b8fc8191b3b77911cd4a29ae"}},"id":"prt_f073571460019Cuow9IdZbvL5W","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","messageID":"msg_f0735367b001G1KCl9Imxmz1VM"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532370846,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_ADnrSVUXXdKl0hc27Kx78pAN","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md","offset":1,"limit":260},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: name: sk-design\n3: description: \"Distinctive, intentional UI design and the full design surface: visual direction, taste, and build for interfaces; color, typography, layout, spacing, hierarchy, and design tokens; animation, transitions, and micro-interactions; accessibility, performance, responsive, theming, and anti-slop design audit with quality scoring; and live-website CSS to Style Reference DESIGN.md extraction. Use to make a UI look custom and polished rather than templated, design a visual system, choreograph motion, audit and harden design quality, or extract a real design system from a live site. The single advisor-routable design skill: it routes to five modes (interface, foundations, motion, audit, md-generator) via mode-registry.json, and each mode holds its own design logic.\"\n4: allowed-tools: [Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Grep, Glob]\n5: version: 1.0.0.0\n6: metadata:\n7:   author: OpenCode\n8:   family: sk-code\n9: ---\n10: \n11: <!-- Keywords: sk-design, design-family, mode-registry, workflowmode, backendkind, reference-base, anti-slop, design-tokens, cognitive-laws, interface-design, frontend-design, visual-design, visual-identity, make-it-look-good, looks-templated, redesign-the-ui, hero-section, ui-build, typography, palette, color-palette, font-pairing, ux-quality-checklist, design-variations, foundations, color-system, oklch, color-token-system, dark-mode, typography-scale, spacing-system, responsive-layout, layout, hierarchy, grid, themes, motion-design, animation, animate-this, transitions, micro-interactions, framer-motion, animatepresence, exit-animation, reduced-motion, morphing-icons, motion-performance, design-audit, ui-critique, accessibility-audit, performance-audit, anti-slop-detection, production-hardening, design-quality-score, P0-P1-design-findings, polish, theming, design.md, design-md, css-extraction, website-design-extraction, design-reference, tokens.json, playwright, design-to-markdown, design-system-generator, css-tokens, color-extraction, typography-extraction, hex-extraction, shadow-extraction, spacing-extraction, design-fidelity, anti-hallucination, extract-design-system, generate-design-md, capture-website-css, design-tokens-from-url, distinctive-interface, intentional-design, polished-ui, refined-ui, custom-not-templated, premium-ui, aesthetic, design-taste, visual-direction, craft, make-it-beautiful, less-generic, redesign-distinctive, smooth-animation, hover-effect, scroll-animation, choreography, interaction-feel, animate-the-menu, transition-design, design-audit, accessibility-audit, design-quality-audit, design-review, design-qa, audit-the-design, review-the-ui, wcag-contrast, ui-quality-review -->\n12: \n13: # Design Family Hub (sk-design)\n14: \n15: One skill, five design modes, one shared reference base. `sk-design` is the public, advisor-routable home for every design persona; the shared design reference base (anti-slop principles, cognitive laws, design-token vocabulary) is the common vocabulary the modes cite. This hub holds NO per-mode design logic — each mode keeps its own contract in its packet, and the hub only routes by `workflowMode` through `mode-registry.json`.\n16: \n17: ---\n18: \n19: ## 1. WHEN TO USE\n20: \n21: Use this skill (through the hub) for any design-family workflow. Invoke it as `sk-design` (optionally with a mode hint such as `motion: <request>`); the hub classifies the request, resolves a mode key, and loads the matching nested packet.\n22: \n23: | Mode | Use it for | Packet |\n24: |------|-----------|--------|\n25: | **interface** | Distinctive, intentional UI direction and build judgment, visual identity, redesign, generic \"make it look good\", interface writing | `sk-design/design-interface/` |\n26: | **foundations** | Static visual-system decisions: color, typography, layout, spacing, hierarchy, responsive adaptation, themes, design tokens | `sk-design/design-foundations/` |\n27: | **motion** | Temporal interaction design: animation, transitions, micro-interactions, motion materials, `AnimatePresence`, reduced motion | `sk-design/design-motion/` |\n28: | **audit** | Design QA and critique: accessibility, performance, responsive, theming, anti-slop detection, scoring, production hardening | `sk-design/design-audit/` |\n29: | **md-generator** | Extract a live website's real CSS into a v3 Style Reference `DESIGN.md` via the embedded extract-write-validate pipeline | `sk-design/design-md-generator/` |\n30: \n31: ### When NOT to Use\n32: - A single quick read/edit with no design judgment — use the relevant skill directly.\n33: - Pure implementation after design direction is settled — hand off to `sk-code`.\n34: - A design transport only (Figma, Open Design) — load the design judgment via this hub first, then use the transport. The transport is never the taste authority.\n35: - The shared reference base itself — it is the vocabulary the modes cite, not a user workflow.\n36: \n37: ---\n38: \n39: ## 2. SMART ROUTING\n40: \n41: Routing is **registry-driven**. `mode-registry.json` is the single source of truth; the hub reads it and does not re-derive the mapping. The advisor routes any design query to the single identity `sk-design`; the hub then picks the mode.\n42: \n43: ### The discriminator\n44: - **`workflowMode`** — the public mode key (every mode): `interface`, `foundations`, `motion`, `audit`, `md-generator`.\n45: - **`backendKind`** — which backend runs the mode: `reference-base` (the four doc-guidance modes cite the shared design reference base) or `playwright-extract` (`md-generator` runs its embedded Playwright CSS-extraction pipeline).\n46: \n47: ### Routing rule\n48: ```\n49: classify the request to a workflowMode (dominant design intent; mode hint like \"motion: ...\" overrides)\n50: read mode-registry.json\n51:   → resolve workflowMode from the hint / classified intent\n52:   → load the mode packet at registry[mode].packet (e.g. sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md)\n53:   → the mode cites the shared reference base, or runs its own backend per registry[mode].backendKind\n54: ```\n55: \n56: Intent classification favors the smallest useful mode. Default a generic \"make this look good\" prompt to **interface** unless the prompt is explicitly foundations (tokens/color/type/layout), motion (animation/transition), audit (critique/accessibility/slop), or md-generator (`DESIGN.md`/style-reference extraction). Pair modes only when the prompt has clearly separate design axes (e.g. interface + motion for a landing page with substantial choreography).\n57: \n58: Per-mode behavior is **not flattened**: each packet keeps its own design judgment, examples, standards, verification, and tool-permission needs. The four doc-guidance modes are read-and-guide; `md-generator` is the only mode that runs an extraction pipeline (Write/Edit/Bash over Playwright).\n59: \n60: ---\n61: \n62: ## 3. HOW IT WORKS\n63: \n64: ### Layout\n65: ```\n66: sk-design/\n67:   SKILL.md               # this routing hub (no per-mode design logic)\n68:   mode-registry.json     # the discriminator + advisorRouting (single source of truth)\n69:   graph-metadata.json    # the ONE advisor identity for the whole skill\n70:   references/            # shared design reference base the hub + modes cite\n71:   design-interface/  design-foundations/  design-motion/  design-audit/  design-md-generator/   # five mode packets\n72: ```\n73: \n74: Each mode packet is self-contained (its own `SKILL.md`, `references/`, `assets/`, and `md-generator`'s extraction backend), with internal paths repointed and **no per-packet `graph-metadata.json`** — only this hub carries one, so the advisor discovers exactly one skill. The mode packet folders are created when the flat skills move under the hub; the hub references those packet paths now.\n75: \n76: ### Backend\n77: The four doc-guidance modes (interface, foundations, motion, audit) consume the shared **design reference base** under `references/` — `anti_slop_principles.md`, `cognitive_laws.md`, `design_token_vocabulary.md` — so anti-slop critique, design-token vocabulary, and cognitive-law rationale stay consistent across modes without duplication. The `md-generator` mode consumes its own embedded Playwright extraction backend instead. The reference base provides shared vocabulary; it must never gain per-mode workflow logic.\n78: \n79: ---\n80: \n81: ## 4. RULES\n82: \n83: ### ALWAYS\n84: - **ALWAYS** resolve a mode through `mode-registry.json`; never hardcode a router mapping in the hub.\n85: - **ALWAYS** keep each mode's design judgment, examples, and verification in its packet — the hub stays logic-free.\n86: - **ALWAYS** keep exactly one `graph-metadata.json` (this hub's) so the advisor sees one skill identity.\n87: - **ALWAYS** give every mode an `advisorRouting` block with a valid `routingClass` and `packetSkillName`.\n88: - **ALWAYS** route a generic design prompt to the smallest useful mode; default to `interface` when no other axis dominates.\n89: \n90: ### NEVER\n91: - **NEVER** add a `graph-metadata.json` or a discoverable skill marker inside a mode packet or the shared reference base.\n92: - **NEVER** embed per-mode design instructions in this hub — that content lives in the packets.\n93: - **NEVER** treat `mcp-figma` or `mcp-open-design` as taste or critique authority; they are transports loaded after the design mode is chosen.\n94: - **NEVER** route pure code, backend, or data work through the design family.\n95: \n96: ### ESCALATE IF\n97: - A new design mode is needed — extend `mode-registry.json` and open a packet; do not bolt logic onto the hub.\n98: - A named mode conflicts with the request's actual intent, or the prompt spans more than three design axes needing an explicit workflow order.\n99: - Brand, accessibility, or production constraints make the requested visual direction unsafe or contradictory.\n100: \n101: ---\n102: \n103: ## 5. REFERENCES\n104: \n105: - Shared reference base: `references/anti_slop_principles.md`, `references/cognitive_laws.md`, `references/design_token_vocabulary.md` (cited by every doc-guidance mode).\n106: - Mode packets: `design-interface/SKILL.md`, `design-foundations/SKILL.md`, `design-motion/SKILL.md`, `design-audit/SKILL.md`, `design-md-generator/SKILL.md` (per-mode detail).\n107: - Registry: `mode-registry.json` (the routing contract).\n108: - Implementation handoff: `sk-code` consumes the design output; `sk-code-review` can audit it after build.\n109: \n110: ---\n111: \n112: ## 6. SUCCESS CRITERIA\n113: \n114: - The hub resolves one primary mode for the request (or a small set only for clearly separate axes).\n115: - The selected mode packet owns the detailed design workflow; the hub stayed routing-only.\n116: - The shared reference base is used only for common vocabulary and cross-mode consistency.\n117: - Exactly one `graph-metadata.json` exists for the whole skill; no packet carries its own.\n118: \n119: ---\n120: \n121: ## 7. INTEGRATION POINTS\n122: \n123: ### Modes\n124: - `interface` — direction, distinctive UI build judgment, interface writing.\n125: - `foundations` — color, typography, layout, responsive systems, tokens.\n126: - `motion` — animation, transitions, micro-interactions, temporal feel.\n127: - `audit` — accessibility, performance, critique, hardening, production readiness.\n128: - `md-generator` — `DESIGN.md` / style-reference extraction other skills consume.\n129: \n130: ### Transports and Consumers\n131: - `mcp-figma` and `mcp-open-design` are transports. Use them after the design mode is chosen.\n132: - `sk-code` consumes design output and implements it in the detected code surface.\n133: - `sk-code-review` can audit implementation quality after design and build work converge.\n134: \n135: ---\n136: \n137: ## 8. RELATED RESOURCES\n138: \n139: - Pattern: `.opencode/skills/sk-doc/references/skill_creation/parent_skills_nested_packets.md` (parent-skill hub + nested packets, the one-graph-metadata invariant).\n140: - Canonical example: `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/` (hub + `mode-registry.json` + mode packets).\n141: - Registry: `mode-registry.json` (this hub's routing contract).\n\n(End of file - total 141 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nname: sk-design\ndescription: \"Distinctive, intentional UI design and the full design surface: visual direction, taste, and build for interfaces; color, typography, layout, spacing, hierarchy, and design tokens; animation, transitions, and micro-interactions; accessibility, performance, responsive, theming, and anti-slop design audit with quality scoring; and live-website CSS to Style Reference DESIGN.md extraction. Use to make a UI look custom and polished rather than templated, design a visual system, choreograph motion, audit and harden design quality, or extract a real design system from a live site. The single advisor-routable design skill: it routes to five modes (interface, foundations, motion, audit, md-generator) via mode-registry.json, and each mode holds its own design logic.\"\nallowed-tools: [Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Grep, Glob]\nversion: 1.0.0.0\nmetadata:\n  author: OpenCode\n  family: sk-code\n---\n\n<!-- Keywords: sk-design, design-family, mode-registry, workflowmode, backendkind, reference-base, anti-slop, design-tokens, cognitive-laws, interface-design, frontend-design, visual-design, visual-identity, make-it-look-good, looks-templated, redesign-the-ui, hero-section, ui-build, typography, palette, color-palette, font-pairing, ux-quality-checklist, design-variations, foundations, color-system, oklch, color-token-system, dark-mode, typography-scale, spacing-system, responsive-layout, layout, hierarchy, grid, themes, motion-design, animation, animate-this, transitions, micro-interactions, framer-motion, animatepresence, exit-animation, reduced-motion, morphing-icons, motion-performance, design-audit, ui-critique, accessibility-audit, performance-audit, anti-slop-detection, production-hardening, design-quality-score, P0-P1-design-findings, polish, theming, design.md, design-md, css-extraction, website-design-extraction, design-reference, tokens.json, playwright, design-to-markdown, design-system-generator, css-tokens, color-extraction, typography-extraction, hex-extraction, shadow-extraction, spacing-extraction, design-fidelity, anti-hallucination, extract-design-system, generate-design-md, capture-website-css, design-tokens-from-url, distinctive-interface, intentional-design, polished-ui, refined-ui, custom-not-templated, premium-ui, aesthetic, design-taste, visual-direction, craft, make-it-beautiful, less-generic, redesign-distinctive, smooth-animation, hover-effect, scroll-animation, choreography, interaction-feel, animate-the-menu, transition-design, design-audit, accessibility-audit, design-quality-audit, design-review, design-qa, audit-the-design, review-the-ui, wcag-contrast, ui-quality-review -->\n\n# Design Family Hub (sk-design)\n\nOne skill, five design modes, one shared reference base. `sk-design` is the public, advisor-routable home for every design persona; the shared design reference base (anti-slop principles, cognitive laws, design-token vocabulary) is the common vocabulary the modes cite. This hub holds NO per-mode design logic — each mode keeps its own contract in its packet, and the hub only routes by `workflowMode` through `mode-registry.json`.\n\n---\n\n## 1. WHEN TO USE\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md","text":"---\nname: sk-design\ndescription: \"Distinctive, intentional UI design and the full design surface: visual direction, taste, and build for interfaces; color, typography, layout, spacing, hierarchy, and design tokens; animation, transitions, and micro-interactions; accessibility, performance, responsive, theming, and anti-slop design audit with quality scoring; and live-website CSS to Style Reference DESIGN.md extraction. Use to make a UI look custom and polished rather than templated, design a visual system, choreograph motion, audit and harden design quality, or extract a real design system from a live site. The single advisor-routable design skill: it routes to five modes (interface, foundations, motion, audit, md-generator) via mode-registry.json, and each mode holds its own design logic.\"\nallowed-tools: [Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Grep, Glob]\nversion: 1.0.0.0\nmetadata:\n  author: OpenCode\n  family: sk-code\n---\n\n<!-- Keywords: sk-design, design-family, mode-registry, workflowmode, backendkind, reference-base, anti-slop, design-tokens, cognitive-laws, interface-design, frontend-design, visual-design, visual-identity, make-it-look-good, looks-templated, redesign-the-ui, hero-section, ui-build, typography, palette, color-palette, font-pairing, ux-quality-checklist, design-variations, foundations, color-system, oklch, color-token-system, dark-mode, typography-scale, spacing-system, responsive-layout, layout, hierarchy, grid, themes, motion-design, animation, animate-this, transitions, micro-interactions, framer-motion, animatepresence, exit-animation, reduced-motion, morphing-icons, motion-performance, design-audit, ui-critique, accessibility-audit, performance-audit, anti-slop-detection, production-hardening, design-quality-score, P0-P1-design-findings, polish, theming, design.md, design-md, css-extraction, website-design-extraction, design-reference, tokens.json, playwright, design-to-markdown, design-system-generator, css-tokens, color-extraction, typography-extraction, hex-extraction, shadow-extraction, spacing-extraction, design-fidelity, anti-hallucination, extract-design-system, generate-design-md, capture-website-css, design-tokens-from-url, distinctive-interface, intentional-design, polished-ui, refined-ui, custom-not-templated, premium-ui, aesthetic, design-taste, visual-direction, craft, make-it-beautiful, less-generic, redesign-distinctive, smooth-animation, hover-effect, scroll-animation, choreography, interaction-feel, animate-the-menu, transition-design, design-audit, accessibility-audit, design-quality-audit, design-review, design-qa, audit-the-design, review-the-ui, wcag-contrast, ui-quality-review -->\n\n# Design Family Hub (sk-design)\n\nOne skill, five design modes, one shared reference base. `sk-design` is the public, advisor-routable home for every design persona; the shared design reference base (anti-slop principles, cognitive laws, design-token vocabulary) is the common vocabulary the modes cite. This hub holds NO per-mode design logic — each mode keeps its own contract in its packet, and the hub only routes by `workflowMode` through `mode-registry.json`.\n\n---\n\n## 1. WHEN TO USE\n\nUse this skill (through the hub) for any design-family workflow. Invoke it as `sk-design` (optionally with a mode hint such as `motion: <request>`); the hub classifies the request, resolves a mode key, and loads the matching nested packet.\n\n| Mode | Use it for | Packet |\n|------|-----------|--------|\n| **interface** | Distinctive, intentional UI direction and build judgment, visual identity, redesign, generic \"make it look good\", interface writing | `sk-design/design-interface/` |\n| **foundations** | Static visual-system decisions: color, typography, layout, spacing, hierarchy, responsive adaptation, themes, design tokens | `sk-design/design-foundations/` |\n| **motion** | Temporal interaction design: animation, transitions, micro-interactions, motion materials, `AnimatePresence`, reduced motion | `sk-design/design-motion/` |\n| **audit** | Design QA and critique: accessibility, performance, responsive, theming, anti-slop detection, scoring, production hardening | `sk-design/design-audit/` |\n| **md-generator** | Extract a live website's real CSS into a v3 Style Reference `DESIGN.md` via the embedded extract-write-validate pipeline | `sk-design/design-md-generator/` |\n\n### When NOT to Use\n- A single quick read/edit with no design judgment — use the relevant skill directly.\n- Pure implementation after design direction is settled — hand off to `sk-code`.\n- A design transport only (Figma, Open Design) — load the design judgment via this hub first, then use the transport. The transport is never the taste authority.\n- The shared reference base itself — it is the vocabulary the modes cite, not a user workflow.\n\n---\n\n## 2. SMART ROUTING\n\nRouting is **registry-driven**. `mode-registry.json` is the single source of truth; the hub reads it and does not re-derive the mapping. The advisor routes any design query to the single identity `sk-design`; the hub then picks the mode.\n\n### The discriminator\n- **`workflowMode`** — the public mode key (every mode): `interface`, `foundations`, `motion`, `audit`, `md-generator`.\n- **`backendKind`** — which backend runs the mode: `reference-base` (the four doc-guidance modes cite the shared design reference base) or `playwright-extract` (`md-generator` runs its embedded Playwright CSS-extraction pipeline).\n\n### Routing rule\n```\nclassify the request to a workflowMode (dominant design intent; mode hint like \"motion: ...\" overrides)\nread mode-registry.json\n  → resolve workflowMode from the hint / classified intent\n  → load the mode packet at registry[mode].packet (e.g. sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md)\n  → the mode cites the shared reference base, or runs its own backend per registry[mode].backendKind\n```\n\nIntent classification favors the smallest useful mode. Default a generic \"make this look good\" prompt to **interface** unless the prompt is explicitly foundations (tokens/color/type/layout), motion (animation/transition), audit (critique/accessibility/slop), or md-generator (`DESIGN.md`/style-reference extraction). Pair modes only when the prompt has clearly separate design axes (e.g. interface + motion for a landing page with substantial choreography).\n\nPer-mode behavior is **not flattened**: each packet keeps its own design judgment, examples, standards, verification, and tool-permission needs. The four doc-guidance modes are read-and-guide; `md-generator` is the only mode that runs an extraction pipeline (Write/Edit/Bash over Playwright).\n\n---\n\n## 3. HOW IT WORKS\n\n### Layout\n```\nsk-design/\n  SKILL.md               # this routing hub (no per-mode design logic)\n  mode-registry.json     # the discriminator + advisorRouting (single source of truth)\n  graph-metadata.json    # the ONE advisor identity for the whole skill\n  references/            # shared design reference base the hub + modes cite\n  design-interface/  design-foundations/  design-motion/  design-audit/  design-md-generator/   # five mode packets\n```\n\nEach mode packet is self-contained (its own `SKILL.md`, `references/`, `assets/`, and `md-generator`'s extraction backend), with internal paths repointed and **no per-packet `graph-metadata.json`** — only this hub carries one, so the advisor discovers exactly one skill. The mode packet folders are created when the flat skills move under the hub; the hub references those packet paths now.\n\n### Backend\nThe four doc-guidance modes (interface, foundations, motion, audit) consume the shared **design reference base** under `references/` — `anti_slop_principles.md`, `cognitive_laws.md`, `design_token_vocabulary.md` — so anti-slop critique, design-token vocabulary, and cognitive-law rationale stay consistent across modes without duplication. The `md-generator` mode consumes its own embedded Playwright extraction backend instead. The reference base provides shared vocabulary; it must never gain per-mode workflow logic.\n\n---\n\n## 4. RULES\n\n### ALWAYS\n- **ALWAYS** resolve a mode through `mode-registry.json`; never hardcode a router mapping in the hub.\n- **ALWAYS** keep each mode's design judgment, examples, and verification in its packet — the hub stays logic-free.\n- **ALWAYS** keep exactly one `graph-metadata.json` (this hub's) so the advisor sees one skill identity.\n- **ALWAYS** give every mode an `advisorRouting` block with a valid `routingClass` and `packetSkillName`.\n- **ALWAYS** route a generic design prompt to the smallest useful mode; default to `interface` when no other axis dominates.\n\n### NEVER\n- **NEVER** add a `graph-metadata.json` or a discoverable skill marker inside a mode packet or the shared reference base.\n- **NEVER** embed per-mode design instructions in this hub — that content lives in the packets.\n- **NEVER** treat `mcp-figma` or `mcp-open-design` as taste or critique authority; they are transports loaded after the design mode is chosen.\n- **NEVER** route pure code, backend, or data work through the design family.\n\n### ESCALATE IF\n- A new design mode is needed — extend `mode-registry.json` and open a packet; do not bolt logic onto the hub.\n- A named mode conflicts with the request's actual intent, or the prompt spans more than three design axes needing an explicit workflow order.\n- Brand, accessibility, or production constraints make the requested visual direction unsafe or contradictory.\n\n---\n\n## 5. REFERENCES\n\n- Shared reference base: `references/anti_slop_principles.md`, `references/cognitive_laws.md`, `references/design_token_vocabulary.md` (cited by every doc-guidance mode).\n- Mode packets: `design-interface/SKILL.md`, `design-foundations/SKILL.md`, `design-motion/SKILL.md`, `design-audit/SKILL.md`, `design-md-generator/SKILL.md` (per-mode detail).\n- Registry: `mode-registry.json` (the routing contract).\n- Implementation handoff: `sk-code` consumes the design output; `sk-code-review` can audit it after build.\n\n---\n\n## 6. SUCCESS CRITERIA\n\n- The hub resolves one primary mode for the request (or a small set only for clearly separate axes).\n- The selected mode packet owns the detailed design workflow; the hub stayed routing-only.\n- The shared reference base is used only for common vocabulary and cross-mode consistency.\n- Exactly one `graph-metadata.json` exists for the whole skill; no packet carries its own.\n\n---\n\n## 7. INTEGRATION POINTS\n\n### Modes\n- `interface` — direction, distinctive UI build judgment, interface writing.\n- `foundations` — color, typography, layout, responsive systems, tokens.\n- `motion` — animation, transitions, micro-interactions, temporal feel.\n- `audit` — accessibility, performance, critique, hardening, production readiness.\n- `md-generator` — `DESIGN.md` / style-reference extraction other skills consume.\n\n### Transports and Consumers\n- `mcp-figma` and `mcp-open-design` are transports. Use them after the design mode is chosen.\n- `sk-code` consumes design output and implements it in the detected code surface.\n- `sk-code-review` can audit implementation quality after design and build work converge.\n\n---\n\n## 8. RELATED RESOURCES\n\n- Pattern: `.opencode/skills/sk-doc/references/skill_creation/parent_skills_nested_packets.md` (parent-skill hub + nested packets, the one-graph-metadata invariant).\n- Canonical example: `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/` (hub + `mode-registry.json` + mode packets).\n- Registry: `mode-registry.json` (this hub's routing contract).","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":141,"totalLines":141,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md","time":{"start":1782532370841,"end":1782532370845}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0b414214e37777ed016a3f4912b9108191ae7143767a94166a"}},"id":"prt_f07357178001eiDu6XHY64P6ry","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","messageID":"msg_f0735367b001G1KCl9Imxmz1VM"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532370856,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_epJnNFAXgJZt8nuLMk6bet9w","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/mode-registry.json","offset":1,"limit":240},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/mode-registry.json</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: {\n2:   \"skill\": \"sk-design\",\n3:   \"version\": \"1.0.0\",\n4:   \"description\": \"Declarative mode registry: the single source of truth for the discriminator (workflowMode/backendKind) PLUS the advisorRouting projection for sk-design. The hub reads this file to resolve a mode; the advisor routes any design query to the single identity sk-design and the hub picks the mode. All five modes route by hub membership (routingClass 'metadata'), so there is no advisor map entry per mode and no merged-identity projection — the advisor does not read this file at runtime.\",\n5:   \"discriminator\": {\n6:     \"workflowMode\": \"Public hub/mode key. Stable identity used by the hub router and this registry. Carried by every mode.\",\n7:     \"backendKind\": \"Which backend runs the mode: reference-base (cites the shared design reference base under references/) or playwright-extract (runs the embedded Playwright CSS-extraction pipeline).\"\n8:   },\n9:   \"advisorRoutingContract\": {\n10:     \"routingClass\": \"How the advisor finds the mode. For sk-design every mode is 'metadata' = resolved by hub membership; the advisor routes the single identity sk-design and the hub picks the mode, so no mode carries an advisor map entry or a merged-identity projection.\",\n11:     \"packetSkillName\": \"The packet's SKILL.md name. The original flat skill name is preserved as packetSkillName; the packet folder is the short mode key, so folder != packetSkillName is grandfathered here and recorded per mode via grandfatheredFolderMismatch.\",\n12:     \"grandfatheredFolderMismatch\": \"true when the packet folder (short mode key, e.g. 'interface') differs from packetSkillName (the preserved flat name, e.g. 'interface'). All five sk-design modes preserve their original flat names, so all five are grandfathered.\"\n13:   },\n14:   \"modes\": [\n15:     {\n16:       \"workflowMode\": \"interface\",\n17:       \"backendKind\": \"reference-base\",\n18:       \"packet\": \"design-interface\",\n19:       \"packetSkillName\": \"design-interface\",\n20:       \"grandfatheredFolderMismatch\": false,\n21:       \"aliases\": [\"interface design\", \"frontend design\", \"visual design\", \"visual identity\", \"make it look good\", \"looks templated\", \"redesign the ui\", \"hero section\", \"ui build\", \"design variations\"],\n22:       \"advisorRouting\": {\n23:         \"routingClass\": \"metadata\",\n24:         \"packetSkillName\": \"design-interface\"\n25:       }\n26:     },\n27:     {\n28:       \"workflowMode\": \"foundations\",\n29:       \"backendKind\": \"reference-base\",\n30:       \"packet\": \"design-foundations\",\n31:       \"packetSkillName\": \"design-foundations\",\n32:       \"grandfatheredFolderMismatch\": false,\n33:       \"aliases\": [\"design foundations\", \"color system\", \"oklch palette\", \"color token system\", \"dark mode palette\", \"typography scale\", \"font pairing\", \"spacing system\", \"responsive layout\", \"design tokens\"],\n34:       \"advisorRouting\": {\n35:         \"routingClass\": \"metadata\",\n36:         \"packetSkillName\": \"design-foundations\"\n37:       }\n38:     },\n39:     {\n40:       \"workflowMode\": \"motion\",\n41:       \"backendKind\": \"reference-base\",\n42:       \"packet\": \"design-motion\",\n43:       \"packetSkillName\": \"design-motion\",\n44:       \"grandfatheredFolderMismatch\": false,\n45:       \"aliases\": [\"motion design\", \"animate this\", \"micro-interactions\",