{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532370964,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_UnptoMDAWPsI7JAneBrCIJqw","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"Mode A|mode A|100 of 100|100/100|motion.*100|score.*100","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public","include":"*.md"},"output":"Found 100 matches (more matches available)\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/agents/orchestrate.md:\n  Line 367: | **Conditions** | `output.confidence` (0-100), `output.type` (\"success\"/\"error\"/\"partial\"), `output.status`, `output.score` (0-100), `output.count` |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/agents/review.md:\n  Line 257: **Output**: pass (bool), score (0-100), breakdown (correctness/security/patterns/maintainability/performance), blockers (P0), required (P1), suggestions (P2), revision_guidance, confidence (HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/agents/ai-council.md:\n  Line 35: ## Deep Mode Availability\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/commands/deep/skill-benchmark.md:\n  Line 66: - **target skill** — the skill id or root to benchmark (must have an `INTENT_SIGNALS` + `RESOURCE_MAP` smart router for Mode A; e.g. the `cli-*` skills).\n\n  Line 69: - **trace mode** — `router` (Mode A, deterministic, default/CI) or `live` (Mode B, BUILT — playbook corpus dispatched through `cli-opencode`).\n\n  Line 112: Mode A (router-replay) scores D1-intra, D2, D3, D5 deterministically; D1-inter (advisor selection) is opt-in via `--advisor-mode=python`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.claude/agents/orchestrate.md:\n  Line 356: | **Conditions** | `output.confidence` (0-100), `output.type` (\"success\"/\"error\"/\"partial\"), `output.status`, `output.score` (0-100), `output.count` |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.claude/agents/review.md:\n  Line 242: **Output**: pass (bool), score (0-100), breakdown (correctness/security/patterns/maintainability/performance), blockers (P0), required (P1), suggestions (P2), revision_guidance, confidence (HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/benchmark/after/skill-benchmark-report.md:\n  Line 12: | D1 intra (router) | 13pts | 100/100 |\n\n  Line 13: | D2 discovery | 20pts | 100/100 |\n\n  Line 34: | Scenario | Tier | Mode A score | First failing stage |\n\n  Line 37: | sk-code-motion-002 | T2 | 69/100 | passed |\n\n  Line 41: - Mode A is the deterministic CI gate; D1-inter (advisor) + D4 (ablation) need live mode.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/benchmark/live-remediated/skill-benchmark-report.md:\n  Line 21: | D5 connectivity (hard gate) | 15pts | 100/100 |\n\n  Line 45: | MR-001 | browser | 100/100 | passed |\n\n  Line 50: - Mode A is the deterministic CI gate; D1-inter (advisor) + D4 (ablation) need live mode.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/benchmark/live/skill-benchmark-report.md:\n  Line 47: - Mode A is the deterministic CI gate; D1-inter (advisor) + D4 (ablation) need live mode.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/commands/memory/search.md:\n  Line 70: Score mandate — one score, one scale, one name: `<score>` is `similarity` on a 0–1 scale rendered to two decimals (`0.79`), and it is the SOLE ranking metric per row. Never render `confidence`, and never render a percentage — divide any percentage-scaled value by 100 before emitting (`79.44` → `0.79`). Do not add a second ranking number under any other name.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/benchmark/baseline/skill-benchmark-report.md:\n  Line 131: - Mode A is the deterministic CI gate; D1-inter (advisor) + D4 (ablation) need live mode.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/benchmark/router-final/skill-benchmark-report.md:\n  Line 21: | D5 connectivity (hard gate) | 15pts | 100/100 |\n\n  Line 50: | RD-001 | routing | 100/100 | passed |\n\n  Line 88: - Mode A is the deterministic CI gate; D1-inter (advisor) + D4 (ablation) need live mode.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/benchmark/live-final/skill-benchmark-report.md:\n  Line 21: | D5 connectivity (hard gate) | 15pts | 100/100 |\n\n  Line 45: | MR-001 | browser | 100/100 | passed |\n\n  Line 50: - Mode A is the deterministic CI gate; D1-inter (advisor) + D4 (ablation) need live mode.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/152-sk-design-md-generator/review/review-report.md:\n  Line 23:   - Evidence: isPass() = `result.score >= 80 && !hasCriticalFailure(result)` (line 445). The pass/exit-code gate never reads claimsScore. Meanwhile two scoring formulas disagree on the weight of a claims warning: the gating `score` (line 413) charges prose-fabrication/section-coverage warnings 1pt each, but `claimsScore` (line 412) charges them 10pt each. A doc with 6 fabrication warnings yields claimsScore=40 (fail) yet score=100-6=94 → isPass()=true. Spec REQ-004-2 requires 'a doc with unverified prose cannot reach a passing combined score on hex-fidelity alone', but the dual score is purely cosmetic at the gate (printResult only prints a soft note when claimsScore<80, line 473).\n\n  Line 24:   - Fix: Make isPass() also require claimsScore >= 80 (or fold a claims-aware penalty into `score`). Otherwise REQ-004-2's anti-fabrication guarantee is not enforced — the 99/100 fabrication case the phase targets can still PASS.\n\n  Line 30: - score (line 413) = `100 - failures*5 - warnings*1` — charges each claims warning (prose-fabrication / section-coverage) only 1pt.\n\n  Line 35: Arithmetic in the finding checks out: a doc with 6 fabrication warnings and no failures yields score = 100-6 = 94 (>=80 → isPass true) yet claimsScore = 100-60 = 40 (well below 80). The doc PASSES the gate despite a failing claims score.\n\n  Line 37: This defeats REQ-004-2 ('a doc with unverified prose cannot reach a passing combined score on hex-fidelity alone') and Success Criterion line 120 ('the combined score drops below pass' for the old 99/100-fabrication anobel stub). The dual score is computed and printed but is cosmetic at the gate.\n\n  Line 53:   - Evidence: The test 'scoring: failures cost 5 pts, warnings cost 1 pt' (line 150) constructs a ValidationResult object literal where `score: Math.max(0, 100 - 2*5 - 1*1)` and then asserts `result.score === 89`. It asserts the test's own inline expression, not validate.ts's scoring logic (validate.ts:411-413). The same hollow pattern recurs in 'score cannot go below 0' (line 182): it computes `Math.max(0, 100 - 21*5)` locally and asserts it equals 0 — validateDesignMd is never invoked. So the actual dual-score formula (valuesScore excludes claims warnings; claimsScore = 100 - claimsWarnings*10; clamp-to-0) is only incidentally covered by the prose test at line 162.\n\n  Line 55:   - Verify: Confirmed against the real code. validate.test.ts:150-160 builds a ValidationResult object literal with score: Math.max(0,100-2*5-1*1) and asserts result.score===89 — asserting its own inline arithmetic, never calling validateDesignMd. validate.test.ts:182-191 computes score=Math.max(0,100-manyFailures.length*5) locally and asserts ===0, also never invoking validateDesignMd (it doesn't even build a result object). Both are hollow tests exercising zero production code. The real implementation (validate.ts:411-413) uses a dual-score formula: valuesScore=100-failures*5-(warnings-claimsWarnings)*1 (excludes prose-fabrication/section-coverage warnings), claimsScore=100-claimsWarnings*10, score=100-failures*5-warnings*1, all clamped to 0. The line-150 literal even hard-codes claimsScore:100 and valuesScore equal to score, which contradicts the real dual-score semantics — so the test encodes a formula different from the implementation. The exact scoring/clamp logic is only incidentally covered by the line-162 prose test, which asserts claimsScore<valuesScore from a real call but pins no exact values. The recommendation (drive validateDesignMd with a known fixture and assert score/valuesScore/claimsScore, plus a >20-failure clamp test) is sound. Severity sits at the P1/P2 boundary (test-quality debt, not a product bug), but P1 is defensible since the dual-score formula is the file's anti-fabrication mechanism and has no exact-value coverage.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/benchmark/d4r-live/skill-benchmark-report.md:\n  Line 17: | D1 intra (router) | 13pts | 100/100 |\n\n  Line 18: | D2 discovery | 20pts | 100/100 |\n\n  Line 21: | D5 connectivity (hard gate) | 15pts | 100/100 |\n\n  Line 50: - Mode A is the deterministic CI gate; D1-inter (advisor) + D4 (ablation) need live mode.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/benchmark/full/skill-benchmark-report.md:\n  Line 12: | D1 intra (router) | 13pts | 100/100 |\n\n  Line 13: | D2 discovery | 20pts | 100/100 |\n\n  Line 37: | Scenario | Tier | Mode A score | First failing stage |\n\n  Line 40: | sk-code-motion-002 | T2 | 55/100 | activated-inter |\n\n  Line 44: - Mode A is the deterministic CI gate; D1-inter (advisor) + D4 (ablation) need live mode.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.claude/agents/ai-council.md:\n  Line 17: ## Deep Mode Availability\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/assets/skill/skill_md_template.md:\n  Line 70: - Structure: 100/100\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/152-sk-design-md-generator/004-validator-semantic-checks/spec.md:\n  Line 65: `validate.ts` runs 6 mechanical checks; none reads a prose sentence. The score conflates value-fidelity with prose-provenance, so a doc with real hexes and invented prose scores 99/100. Stability gating only applies to colors, so an L4 shadow/gradient passes.\n\n  Line 83: - Dual-score split: `valuesScore` (mechanical hex/section fidelity) + `claimsScore` (prose provenance) so 99/100 can't be earned on hex-tracing while prose is unverified.\n\n  Line 120: - Running the validator on the OLD anobel stub (the one that scored 99/100 with fabrications) now flags the empty §6 and the unverified prose; the combined score drops below pass.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/mcp-code-mode/SKILL.md:\n  Line 46: | Scenario                     | Code Mode Approach                                                      | Benefit                     |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-opencode/changelog/v1.3.6.0.md:\n  Line 39: - All 5 frameworks scored **100% correctness** (MiMo is frontier-class), so the discriminator is **format adherence + token efficiency, not correctness.** Lean output/audience-framed prompts suppress the explanatory preamble that CIDI/RCAF/TIDD-EC leak on harder tasks (TIDD-EC ~2.4× longer output).\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/151-sk-design-md-generator/review/review-report.md:\n  Line 23:   - Evidence: isPass() = `result.score >= 80 && !hasCriticalFailure(result)` (line 445). The pass/exit-code gate never reads claimsScore. Meanwhile two scoring formulas disagree on the weight of a claims warning: the gating `score` (line 413) charges prose-fabrication/section-coverage warnings 1pt each, but `claimsScore` (line 412) charges them 10pt each. A doc with 6 fabrication warnings yields claimsScore=40 (fail) yet score=100-6=94 → isPass()=true. Spec REQ-004-2 requires 'a doc with unverified prose cannot reach a passing combined score on hex-fidelity alone', but the dual score is purely cosmetic at the gate (printResult only prints a soft note when claimsScore<80, line 473).\n\n  Line 24:   - Fix: Make isPass() also require claimsScore >= 80 (or fold a claims-aware penalty into `score`). Otherwise REQ-004-2's anti-fabrication guarantee is not enforced — the 99/100 fabrication case the phase targets can still PASS.\n\n  Line 30: - score (line 413) = `100 - failures*5 - warnings*1` — charges each claims warning (prose-fabrication / section-coverage) only 1pt.\n\n  Line 35: Arithmetic in the finding checks out: a doc with 6 fabrication warnings and no failures yields score = 100-6 = 94 (>=80 → isPass true) yet claimsScore = 100-60 = 40 (well below 80). The doc PASSES the gate despite a failing claims score.\n\n  Line 37: This defeats REQ-004-2 ('a doc with unverified prose cannot reach a passing combined score on hex-fidelity alone') and Success Criterion line 120 ('the combined score drops below pass' for the old 99/100-fabrication anobel stub). The dual score is computed and printed but is cosmetic at the gate.\n\n  Line 53:   - Evidence: The test 'scoring: failures cost 5 pts, warnings cost 1 pt' (line 150) constructs a ValidationResult object literal where `score: Math.max(0, 100 - 2*5 - 1*1)` and then asserts `result.score === 89`. It asserts the test's own inline expression, not validate.ts's scoring logic (validate.ts:411-413). The same hollow pattern recurs in 'score cannot go below 0' (line 182): it computes `Math.max(0, 100 - 21*5)` locally and asserts it equals 0 — validateDesignMd is never invoked. So the actual dual-score formula (valuesScore excludes claims warnings; claimsScore = 100 - claimsWarnings*10; clamp-to-0) is only incidentally covered by the prose test at line 162.\n\n  Line 55:   - Verify: Confirmed against the real code. validate.test.ts:150-160 builds a ValidationResult object literal with score: Math.max(0,100-2*5-1*1) and asserts result.score===89 — asserting its own inline arithmetic, never calling validateDesignMd. validate.test.ts:182-191 computes score=Math.max(0,100-manyFailures.length*5) locally and asserts ===0, also never invoking validateDesignMd (it doesn't even build a result object). Both are hollow tests exercising zero production code. The real implementation (validate.ts:411-413) uses a dual-score formula: valuesScore=100-failures*5-(warnings-claimsWarnings)*1 (excludes prose-fabrication/section-coverage warnings), claimsScore=100-claimsWarnings*10, score=100-failures*5-warnings*1, all clamped to 0. The line-150 literal even hard-codes claimsScore:100 and valuesScore equal to score, which contradicts the real dual-score semantics — so the test encodes a formula different from the implementation. The exact scoring/clamp logic is only incidentally covered by the line-162 prose test, which asserts claimsScore<valuesScore from a real call but pins no exact values. The recommendation (drive validateDesignMd with a known fixture and assert score/valuesScore/claimsScore, plus a >20-failure clamp test) is sound. Severity sits at the P1/P2 boundary (test-quality debt, not a product bug), but P1 is defensible since the dual-score formula is the file's anti-fabrication mechanism and has no exact-value coverage.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/152-sk-design-md-generator/research/research-plan.md:\n  Line 18: A1 claims-to-token provenance: force every interpretive sentence to cite a tokens.json field; how validate.ts enforces. A2 hard check: forbid word \"consistent\" unless a11yTokens.focusIndicator.consistent==true AND focusStyles.length>0. A3 named-principle (gradient-depth/chromatic-depth) must cite tokens.gradients[]/shadowTokens[] or fail. A4 prompt \"report absence, never invent\" clause for derived/boolean fields. A5 WRITE emits claims.json sidecar (claim->token key) for mechanical verify. A6 extend checkStabilityGating beyond colors to shadows/gradients/components. A7 enforce quality_checklist banned-word/adjective list in code (currently prose-only). A8 reconsider mandated \"comparative framing\" (claims about OTHER systems = structural fabrication). A9 constrain named-principle vocabulary to token-derived allowlist. A10 split score into \"values present\" vs \"claims true\" so 99/100 can't be earned on hex-tracing alone. A11 structured-output mode for high-risk sections (depth/focus/motion philosophy). A12 invert checkUnknownFonts to strict allowlist. A13 per-section evidence ledger in cardinal-rules card + prompt. A14 targeted phrase check \"focus is consistent\" when focusIndicator.style=={}. A15 post-write adversarial self-review listing value-less sentences before VALIDATE.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/README.md:\n  Line 92: The Documentation Quality Index scores a document from 0 to 100. Structure is worth 40 points (checklist pass rate, heading hierarchy, section completeness). Content is worth 30 points (word count in the right range, heading density, code examples, links and tables). Style is worth 30 points (H2 format, section dividers, intro paragraph and HVR compliance). The four bands tell you where you stand:\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/150-parent-nested-skill-pattern/improvement-research/iterations/iteration-004.md:\n  Line 78: - **The benchmark's honesty about unscored dimensions** (Mode A normalizes over measured dims, `score-skill-benchmark.cjs:194-204`) is well-engineered; the only gap is mode-precision visibility (P2), not the scoring math.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/152-sk-design-md-generator/research/iterations/iteration-034.md:\n  Line 7: 1. **[P0] proof.ts freshness/drift score → DESIGN.md header** — proof.ts computes a coverage score (0-100%) by sampling live-site pixels against the token palette (OKLCH deltaE<12, excluding image regions). This is a drift detector: re-running proof.ts post-extraction reveals whether the source site changed since extraction. The score is currently ephemeral (proof.html/proof-data.json). Borrowable idea: embed a 'freshness stamp' in DESIGN.md header — extractionDate, lastProofDate, coverageScore, driftStatus (FRESH/STALE/UNKNOWN). Consumers (frontend agents, CI) can gate on driftStatus before trusting tokens. Where: DESIGN.md YAML frontmatter or §0 header block.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/152-sk-design-md-generator/research/iterations/iteration-010.md:\n  Line 14:    - Recommendation: Design a SectionCoverageReport with shape: {sections:{number,title,tokenField,tokenCount,isEmpty,inventionRisk:none|low|medium|high}[], emptySections:string[], summary:{totalSections,backedSections,emptySections,thinSections}}. Implement as a new check (checkSectionCoverage) in validate.ts — it already reads both DESIGN.md and tokens.json. Map each of the 17 DESIGN.md sections to its DesignTokens fields (§2→colorTokens+colorRelationships, §3→typographyLevels+fontInfo, §6→shadowTokens+gradients, §6.5→motionSystem, §10→breakpoints, §11→components[*].variants[*].hoverChanges, §12→iconSystem, §2.5→darkMode, etc.). Any section with an empty/null backing token set is flagged HIGH invention risk. This is a near-zero-cost mechanical hallucination detector that catches 100% of empty-section fabrication sites.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/150-parent-nested-skill-pattern/improvement-research/iterations/iteration-002.md:\n  Line 14: # i02 — Mode Architecture & Boundaries (READ-ONLY improvement research)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/152-sk-design-md-generator/research/iterations/iteration-041.md:\n  Line 16: 4. **[P1] a11y-extract: altTextCoverage returns 100% when no images exist** — default-fabrication — Line 246: when total === 0, percentage defaults to 100. A site with zero images gets a perfect alt-text score. The DESIGN.md a11y section would claim 100% coverage without any images to assess.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/152-sk-design-md-generator/research/iterations/iteration-004.md:\n  Line 13: 3. **[P0] A10: single score conflates value fidelity with prose provenance** — validateDesignMd (line 347) computes score = 100 - failures*5 - warnings*1. A DESIGN.md with all real hexes, complete sections, and proper format — but prose full of 'A sleek, modern design system with elegant depth principles' — scores 99/100 and passes (≥80, no critical failures). The score gives no signal that the prose is unverified filler. There is no mechanical check that prose claims (color roles, typography rationale, depth philosophy) trace back to actual token data. The prose-provenance gap is the primary hallucination vector the validator misses.\n\n  Line 14:    - Recommendation: Split into two scores in ValidationResult: { valuesScore: number, claimsScore: number, score: number }. valuesScore = existing scoring logic (hex presence, sections, format, stability gating — all mechanical). claimsScore = 100 minus penalties from: (a) checkProseDiscipline warnings (A7 above), (b) checkProseClaims — scan descriptive paragraphs for numeric assertions (hex, px, rem, ratio) and verify each against tokens; each unverified assertion is a failure (-5), (c) checkSemanticGrounding — verify color role names in prose ('primary', 'accent', 'surface') map to actual token roles, not invented labels. score = Math.round(valuesScore * 0.6 + claimsScore * 0.4). Update isPass to require both valuesScore ≥ 80 AND claimsScore ≥ 60. Add 'unverified-claim' and 'ungrounded-semantic' to failure types (not critical — they affect claimsScore only, not hard-fail).\n\n  Line 40: The validator's mechanical reach is narrow: stability gating only covers colors (A6), banned-word discipline exists only as prose checklists with zero code enforcement (A7), and the single score lets prose-only hallucinations pass at 99/100 (A10). The font check's explicit skip-list is a moderate risk (A12). All four findings have concrete mechanical fixes — the banned-word check uses sentence-level numeric anchors for false-positive suppression, the dual score splits value fidelity from prose provenance, and the stability extension reuses existing stability classification infrastructure already present in cluster.ts.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/references/global/validation.md:\n  Line 180: The `extract_structure.py` script computes a **Document Quality Index (DQI)** - a 100% deterministic score from 0-100 based on measurable document attributes. This replaces subjective AI-only assessment with quantifiable metrics.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/152-sk-design-md-generator/research/iterations/iteration-025.md:\n  Line 13: 3. **[P0] validate.ts:57-93,318-349 — graded validator with critical-failure gating** — The validator already produces a graded score (0-100: -5 per failure, -1 per warning) AND enforces CRITICAL_FAILURE_TYPES (phantom-color, content-color, missing-section) that hard-fail regardless of score. A single fabricated hex triggers FAIL even if all other checks pass. This is already an evidence-completeness validator, not purely binary: it distinguishes between format issues (warnings: -1) and fabrication (failures: -5, gate-failing). The score degradations per-error type create a natural severity scale.\n\n  Line 22: 6. **[P2] design-boundary-detect.ts:228-311 — cross-site similarity scores per dimension** — The boundary detector computes similarity scores per dimension (font, color, spacing, radius, component, shadow) between site groups. These are inherently confidence signals: a site with a single page scores 100 on everything (no variance = low evidence of system-ness). Multi-domain extractions produce real similarity scores that reveal where a design system is consistent vs. fragmented — the thin dimensions signal invention-prone areas.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/mcp-code-mode/references/workflows.md:\n  Line 811: ### Code Mode Approach\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/151-sk-design-md-generator/004-validator-semantic-checks/spec.md:\n  Line 65: `validate.ts` runs 6 mechanical checks; none reads a prose sentence. The score conflates value-fidelity with prose-provenance, so a doc with real hexes and invented prose scores 99/100. Stability gating only applies to colors, so an L4 shadow/gradient passes.\n\n  Line 83: - Dual-score split: `valuesScore` (mechanical hex/section fidelity) + `claimsScore` (prose provenance) so 99/100 can't be earned on hex-tracing while prose is unverified.\n\n  Line 120: - Running the validator on the OLD anobel stub (the one that scored 99/100 with fabrications) now flags the empty §6 and the unverified prose; the combined score drops below pass.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/152-sk-design-md-generator/research/iterations/iteration-026.md:\n  Line 46: 14. **[P2] dual-score-split-value-fidelity-vs-prose-provenance** — Single score (validate.ts:347) conflates value fidelity with prose provenance. A doc with all real hexes but full fabricated prose scores 99/100. Split into valuesScore (mechanical) + claimsScore (prose quality). Iter-024: valuable but adds complexity — defer until prose checks are implemented.\n\n  Line 47:    - Recommendation: validate.ts — ValidationResult gains valuesScore/claimsScore alongside score. valuesScore = existing mechanical logic. claimsScore = 100 minus penalties from checkProseDiscipline warnings + future source-sentinel checks. isPass adds claimsScore ≥ 60 gate. Guard: dual score only activates once prose checks exist — no impact on current pipeline until then.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/152-sk-design-md-generator/research/iterations/iteration-009.md:\n  Line 74: 8. **[P0] A-i: altTextCoverage returns 100% when zero images exist** — a11y-extract.ts:224-249: when document.querySelectorAll('img') returns an empty NodeList, total=0 and percentage returns 100 (line 246: `total > 0 ? ... : 100`). This fabricates a perfect score from absence of data — an empty page gets \"100% alt text coverage\" which is both misleading and indistinguishable from a page where every image genuinely has alt text.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/152-sk-design-md-generator/research/iterations/iteration-029.md:\n  Line 43: 13. **[P1] Section evidence grading (per-section completeness)** — Already partially exists — validate.ts graded score (0-100) with critical gating. Next step: per-section evidence-completeness comparing writer claims against backing tokens.json. Adoption cost: MEDIUM (~60 LOC new checkEvidenceCompleteness in validate.ts).\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/152-sk-design-md-generator/research/research.md:\n  Line 9: The core defect: `validate.ts` awards 99/100 scores to DESIGN.md outputs containing wholesale prose fabrication. The validator performs 6 checks — phantom-color hex-tracing, stability-gating, unknown-font detection, format-consistency, section-header counting, and content presence — but **zero checks read a prose sentence against token ground truth** (`validate.ts:318-350`). A doc scoring 99/100 can contain \"A sleek, modern design with elegant depth principles\" — none of which has corresponding fields in `tokens.json` (`iter-026:#6`).\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/151-sk-design-md-generator/research/research-plan.md:\n  Line 18: A1 claims-to-token provenance: force every interpretive sentence to cite a tokens.json field; how validate.ts enforces. A2 hard check: forbid word \"consistent\" unless a11yTokens.focusIndicator.consistent==true AND focusStyles.length>0. A3 named-principle (gradient-depth/chromatic-depth) must cite tokens.gradients[]/shadowTokens[] or fail. A4 prompt \"report absence, never invent\" clause for derived/boolean fields. A5 WRITE emits claims.json sidecar (claim->token key) for mechanical verify. A6 extend checkStabilityGating beyond colors to shadows/gradients/components. A7 enforce quality_checklist banned-word/adjective list in code (currently prose-only). A8 reconsider mandated \"comparative framing\" (claims about OTHER systems = structural fabrication). A9 constrain named-principle vocabulary to token-derived allowlist. A10 split score into \"values present\" vs \"claims true\" so 99/100 can't be earned on hex-tracing alone. A11 structured-output mode for high-risk sections (depth/focus/motion philosophy). A12 invert checkUnknownFonts to strict allowlist. A13 per-section evidence ledger in cardinal-rules card + prompt. A14 targeted phrase check \"focus is consistent\" when focusIndicator.style=={}. A15 post-write adversarial self-review listing value-less sentences before VALIDATE.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/151-sk-design-md-generator/research/iterations/iteration-034.md:\n  Line 7: 1. **[P0] proof.ts freshness/drift score → DESIGN.md header** — proof.ts computes a coverage score (0-100%) by sampling live-site pixels against the token palette (OKLCH deltaE<12, excluding image regions). This is a drift detector: re-running proof.ts post-extraction reveals whether the source site changed since extraction. The score is currently ephemeral (proof.html/proof-data.json). Borrowable idea: embed a 'freshness stamp' in DESIGN.md header — extractionDate, lastProofDate, coverageScore, driftStatus (FRESH/STALE/UNKNOWN). Consumers (frontend agents, CI) can gate on driftStatus before trusting tokens. Where: DESIGN.md YAML frontmatter or §0 header block.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/151-sk-design-md-generator/research/iterations/iteration-010.md:\n  Line 14:    - Recommendation: Design a SectionCoverageReport with shape: {sections:{number,title,tokenField,tokenCount,isEmpty,inventionRisk:none|low|medium|high}[], emptySections:string[], summary:{totalSections,backedSections,emptySections,thinSections}}. Implement as a new check (checkSectionCoverage) in validate.ts — it already reads both DESIGN.md and tokens.json. Map each of the 17 DESIGN.md sections to its DesignTokens fields (§2→colorTokens+colorRelationships, §3→typographyLevels+fontInfo, §6→shadowTokens+gradients, §6.5→motionSystem, §10→breakpoints, §11→components[*].variants[*].hoverChanges, §12→iconSystem, §2.5→darkMode, etc.). Any section with an empty/null backing token set is flagged HIGH invention risk. This is a near-zero-cost mechanical hallucination detector that catches 100% of empty-section fabrication sites.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/