{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532404574,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_cuV14oSXa4O3Qd1BTHYNAStj","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"motion|AnimatePresence|animation|transition","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/014-routing-benchmark/design-interface","include":"*.json"},"output":"No files found","metadata":{"matches":0,"truncated":false},"title":"motion|AnimatePresence|animation|transition","time":{"start":1782532404563,"end":1782532404573}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0c58cc7090c2c656016a3f49347eac8191bd5a865e6e6a4aa0"}},"id":"prt_f0735f524001uQUU1C5mamVNan","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","messageID":"msg_f0735b56d001CqC8DrAS2yUPOC"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532404607,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_xf43a1fLZ5POKJB072SmweyS","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"motion|AnimatePresence|animation|transition","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/014-routing-benchmark/design-interface","include":"*.md"},"output":"No files found","metadata":{"matches":0,"truncated":false},"title":"motion|AnimatePresence|animation|transition","time":{"start":1782532404593,"end":1782532404606}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0c58cc7090c2c656016a3f49347ebc8191832c91951e28186b"}},"id":"prt_f0735f568001Y02LUadoSpBah6","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","messageID":"msg_f0735b56d001CqC8DrAS2yUPOC"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532404610,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_jGSECyIubPXcl1Xx3pv70gNL","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/register.md","offset":1,"limit":220},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/register.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Brand-vs-Product Operating Register\n3: description: The shared sk-design operating register. Declare whether a design IS the product or SERVES it, then read the six downstream dials that decision sets.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"brand vs product register\"\n6:   - \"design operating register\"\n7:   - \"design is the product\"\n8:   - \"design serves the product\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: general\n11: version: 1.0.0.0\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Brand-vs-Product Operating Register\n15: \n16: The first design decision, before color, type, layout, or motion: is this surface a Brand surface or a Product surface? That one call sets six downstream dials. Skipping it is the most common reason design output drifts to a generic default.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n21: \n22: ### Purpose\n23: \n24: Give every design mode one shared, up-front decision that calibrates the rest of the work. \"Brand\" and \"Product\" are not styles, they are operating postures. The register names the posture once and the six dials inherit it, so a landing page and an admin dashboard never get the same defaults by accident.\n25: \n26: ### Usage\n27: \n28: Set the register at the start of any design task, before the mode-specific workflow runs. Each mode (interface, foundations, motion, audit, md-generator) reads the register and applies the dial settings for the chosen posture. The register is shared vocabulary, not a sixth mode and not a replacement for mode workflows.\n29: \n30: ---\n31: \n32: ## 2. THE REGISTER DECISION\n33: \n34: A surface takes one of two postures:\n35: \n36: - **Brand (design IS the product).** Marketing sites, landing pages, campaigns, long-form content, portfolios. The design is the thing being consumed, so expression, identity and a memorable moment are the job.\n37: - **Product (design SERVES the product).** App UI, admin, dashboards, tools, settings, forms. The design carries the user to a task, so clarity, density and consistency are the job.\n38: \n39: ### How to pick (first match wins)\n40: \n41: 1. **Task cue.** Words in the request like \"landing page\", \"campaign\" and \"portfolio\" point to Brand. Words like \"dashboard\", \"admin\", \"settings\" and \"tool\" point to Product.\n42: 2. **Surface in focus.** The actual page, route, or file being worked on, even inside a mixed app. A marketing page inside a product app is still Brand.\n43: 3. **Declared register.** A `register` field in the project's PRODUCT.md or DESIGN.md, when present, is authoritative.\n44: \n45: A mixed product has both postures: the marketing surface is Brand, the app shell is Product. Set the register per surface, not per project.\n46: \n47: ---\n48: \n49: ## 3. THE SIX DIALS\n50: \n51: The register sets these six. When the surface is unlabeled and internal, Product is the safer default. Brand is the default only when the surface is clearly the thing being sold.\n52: \n53: | Dial | Brand (design IS the product) | Product (design SERVES the product) |\n54: |---|---|---|\n55: | **Density** | Generous and expressive, with room for one big move | Information-dense and efficient, whitespace earns its place |\n56: | **Motion budget** | Motion is voice: one well-rehearsed entrance beats scattered reveals, with scroll motion reserved for moments that earn it | 150 to 250 ms state transitions only, no page-load choreography, motion conveys feedback, reveal, loading and view changes |\n57: | **Color dosage** | Palette is voice: Committed, Full, or Drenched strategies may exceed the 10% accent rule | Semantic-first and almost always Restrained, accent reserved for primary action, selection and state, never decoration |\n58: | **Copy register** | Expressive and voice-led, the words carry identity | Plain, functional and consistent, one copy register across every screen |\n59: | **Anti-slop strictness** | Reject the brand defaults: cream or sand body background, an eyebrow above every section, numbered section scaffolding, over-rounded cards | Reject the product defaults: low-contrast muted-gray text, color used as decoration, undifferentiated card grids |\n60: | **Audit severity** | Weight distinctiveness and voice, a generic-but-functional brand surface is a real finding | Weight affordance, accessibility and consistency, an expressive-but-unclear product surface is a real finding |\n61: \n62: ### The color-strategy axis\n63: \n64: Color dosage resolves to one of four strategies, ordered by how much color carries the surface:\n65: \n66: - **Restrained**: tinted neutrals plus one accent at 10% or less. The Product default.\n67: - **Committed**: one saturated color carries 30 to 60% of the surface. The Brand default for identity-driven pages.\n68: - **Full palette**: three to four named color roles, each used deliberately. Brand campaigns and Product data visualization.\n69: - **Drenched**: the surface itself is the color. Brand heroes and campaign pages only.\n70: \n71: ---\n72: \n73: ## 4. MODE USAGE\n74: \n75: - **interface** reads the register first, then sets density, the motion budget and the color strategy for direction and build.\n76: - **foundations** reads the register to choose the color strategy and the density of the token system (spacing rhythm, type scale).\n77: - **motion** reads the motion-budget dial to decide whether a surface gets choreography or only state transitions.\n78: - **audit** reads the audit-severity dial so a finding is weighted by posture: distinctiveness for Brand, affordance and consistency for Product.\n79: - **md-generator** records the register of the site it extracts, so a captured Style Reference carries the posture forward.\n\n(End of file - total 79 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Brand-vs-Product Operating Register\ndescription: The shared sk-design operating register. Declare whether a design IS the product or SERVES it, then read the six downstream dials that decision sets.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"brand vs product register\"\n  - \"design operating register\"\n  - \"design is the product\"\n  - \"design serves the product\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Brand-vs-Product Operating Register\n\nThe first design decision, before color, type, layout, or motion: is this surface a Brand surface or a Product surface? That one call sets six downstream dials. Skipping it is the most common reason design output drifts to a generic default.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/register.md","text":"---\ntitle: Brand-vs-Product Operating Register\ndescription: The shared sk-design operating register. Declare whether a design IS the product or SERVES it, then read the six downstream dials that decision sets.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"brand vs product register\"\n  - \"design operating register\"\n  - \"design is the product\"\n  - \"design serves the product\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Brand-vs-Product Operating Register\n\nThe first design decision, before color, type, layout, or motion: is this surface a Brand surface or a Product surface? That one call sets six downstream dials. Skipping it is the most common reason design output drifts to a generic default.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nGive every design mode one shared, up-front decision that calibrates the rest of the work. \"Brand\" and \"Product\" are not styles, they are operating postures. The register names the posture once and the six dials inherit it, so a landing page and an admin dashboard never get the same defaults by accident.\n\n### Usage\n\nSet the register at the start of any design task, before the mode-specific workflow runs. Each mode (interface, foundations, motion, audit, md-generator) reads the register and applies the dial settings for the chosen posture. The register is shared vocabulary, not a sixth mode and not a replacement for mode workflows.\n\n---\n\n## 2. THE REGISTER DECISION\n\nA surface takes one of two postures:\n\n- **Brand (design IS the product).** Marketing sites, landing pages, campaigns, long-form content, portfolios. The design is the thing being consumed, so expression, identity and a memorable moment are the job.\n- **Product (design SERVES the product).** App UI, admin, dashboards, tools, settings, forms. The design carries the user to a task, so clarity, density and consistency are the job.\n\n### How to pick (first match wins)\n\n1. **Task cue.** Words in the request like \"landing page\", \"campaign\" and \"portfolio\" point to Brand. Words like \"dashboard\", \"admin\", \"settings\" and \"tool\" point to Product.\n2. **Surface in focus.** The actual page, route, or file being worked on, even inside a mixed app. A marketing page inside a product app is still Brand.\n3. **Declared register.** A `register` field in the project's PRODUCT.md or DESIGN.md, when present, is authoritative.\n\nA mixed product has both postures: the marketing surface is Brand, the app shell is Product. Set the register per surface, not per project.\n\n---\n\n## 3. THE SIX DIALS\n\nThe register sets these six. When the surface is unlabeled and internal, Product is the safer default. Brand is the default only when the surface is clearly the thing being sold.\n\n| Dial | Brand (design IS the product) | Product (design SERVES the product) |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Density** | Generous and expressive, with room for one big move | Information-dense and efficient, whitespace earns its place |\n| **Motion budget** | Motion is voice: one well-rehearsed entrance beats scattered reveals, with scroll motion reserved for moments that earn it | 150 to 250 ms state transitions only, no page-load choreography, motion conveys feedback, reveal, loading and view changes |\n| **Color dosage** | Palette is voice: Committed, Full, or Drenched strategies may exceed the 10% accent rule | Semantic-first and almost always Restrained, accent reserved for primary action, selection and state, never decoration |\n| **Copy register** | Expressive and voice-led, the words carry identity | Plain, functional and consistent, one copy register across every screen |\n| **Anti-slop strictness** | Reject the brand defaults: cream or sand body background, an eyebrow above every section, numbered section scaffolding, over-rounded cards | Reject the product defaults: low-contrast muted-gray text, color used as decoration, undifferentiated card grids |\n| **Audit severity** | Weight distinctiveness and voice, a generic-but-functional brand surface is a real finding | Weight affordance, accessibility and consistency, an expressive-but-unclear product surface is a real finding |\n\n### The color-strategy axis\n\nColor dosage resolves to one of four strategies, ordered by how much color carries the surface:\n\n- **Restrained**: tinted neutrals plus one accent at 10% or less. The Product default.\n- **Committed**: one saturated color carries 30 to 60% of the surface. The Brand default for identity-driven pages.\n- **Full palette**: three to four named color roles, each used deliberately. Brand campaigns and Product data visualization.\n- **Drenched**: the surface itself is the color. Brand heroes and campaign pages only.\n\n---\n\n## 4. MODE USAGE\n\n- **interface** reads the register first, then sets density, the motion budget and the color strategy for direction and build.\n- **foundations** reads the register to choose the color strategy and the density of the token system (spacing rhythm, type scale).\n- **motion** reads the motion-budget dial to decide whether a surface gets choreography or only state transitions.\n- **audit** reads the audit-severity dial so a finding is weighted by posture: distinctiveness for Brand, affordance and consistency for Product.\n- **md-generator** records the register of the site it extracts, so a captured Style Reference carries the posture forward.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":79,"totalLines":79,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/register.md","time":{"start":1782532404601,"end":1782532404609}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0c58cc7090c2c656016a3f49347ec48191912c5317ed191604"}},"id":"prt_f0735f572001qVyBju0dBYMhYL","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","messageID":"msg_f0735b56d001CqC8DrAS2yUPOC"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532404711,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_NAUkxUly2lSS5NuclbEg6SIi","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/anti_slop_principles.md","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/anti_slop_principles.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Anti-Slop Design Principles\n3: description: Shared principles for detecting and avoiding generic AI-default visual decisions across the design skill family.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"anti-slop design\"\n6:   - \"avoid AI default design\"\n7:   - \"generic UI critique\"\n8:   - \"design slop test\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: general\n11: version: 1.0.0.0\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Anti-Slop Design Principles\n15: \n16: Shared vocabulary for design children to detect and avoid generic AI-default visual decisions.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n21: \n22: ### Purpose\n23: \n24: Give every `sk-design-*` child a common language for spotting and rejecting median web defaults. This reference is shared vocabulary, not a replacement for child-owned workflow guidance.\n25: \n26: ### Usage\n27: \n28: Cite these principles during direction critique, token review, motion planning, and audit findings. Children own the detailed workflow that applies them.\n29: \n30: ---\n31: \n32: ## 2. Principle Set\n33: \n34: 1. **Ground before styling.** Name the subject, audience, and one job before choosing color, type, layout, or motion.\n35: 2. **Spend the free axis deliberately.** If the brief does not constrain an axis, use it to make a specific choice instead of selecting the median web default.\n36: 3. **One memorable move beats scattered decoration.** Pick a signature element and let supporting details stay quiet.\n37: 4. **Tokens must explain themselves.** A palette, type scale, spacing rhythm, or motion curve should map to the product's purpose, not to a fashionable preset.\n38: 5. **Remove ornamental numbering.** Avoid `01 / 02 / 03`, fake process markers, and section chrome unless the content is genuinely sequential.\n39: 6. **Respect affordance before novelty.** Distinctive design still needs clear hierarchy, visible focus, legible contrast, and predictable interaction targets.\n40: 7. **Critique the category default, then deviate.** Name the common visual trope for the product category and choose what to keep, bend, or reject.\n41: 8. **Make restraint visible.** If every element competes for attention, the design has no focal point.\n42: \n43: ---\n44: \n45: ## 3. Common AI-Default Smells\n46: \n47: - Generic cream background, editorial serif headline, terracotta accent, and soft card shadows without a brief-specific reason.\n48: - Near-black page with one acid accent and oversized geometric gradients as the only identity.\n49: - Hairline-heavy broadsheet layout where the content has no editorial or archival premise.\n50: - Repeated glassmorphism, blur, glow, or mesh gradients used as decoration rather than structure.\n51: - Motion on many small parts instead of one choreographed moment.\n52: \n53: ---\n54: \n55: ## 4. Child Usage\n56: \n57: - `interface` uses this reference during direction critique.\n58: - `foundations` uses it to test whether tokens are purposeful.\n59: - `motion` uses it to avoid scattered animation.\n60: - `audit` uses it as slop-detection vocabulary.\n\n(End of file - total 60 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Anti-Slop Design Principles\ndescription: Shared principles for detecting and avoiding generic AI-default visual decisions across the design skill family.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"anti-slop design\"\n  - \"avoid AI default design\"\n  - \"generic UI critique\"\n  - \"design slop test\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Anti-Slop Design Principles\n\nShared vocabulary for design children to detect and avoid generic AI-default visual decisions.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/anti_slop_principles.md","text":"---\ntitle: Anti-Slop Design Principles\ndescription: Shared principles for detecting and avoiding generic AI-default visual decisions across the design skill family.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"anti-slop design\"\n  - \"avoid AI default design\"\n  - \"generic UI critique\"\n  - \"design slop test\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Anti-Slop Design Principles\n\nShared vocabulary for design children to detect and avoid generic AI-default visual decisions.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nGive every `sk-design-*` child a common language for spotting and rejecting median web defaults. This reference is shared vocabulary, not a replacement for child-owned workflow guidance.\n\n### Usage\n\nCite these principles during direction critique, token review, motion planning, and audit findings. Children own the detailed workflow that applies them.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Principle Set\n\n1. **Ground before styling.** Name the subject, audience, and one job before choosing color, type, layout, or motion.\n2. **Spend the free axis deliberately.** If the brief does not constrain an axis, use it to make a specific choice instead of selecting the median web default.\n3. **One memorable move beats scattered decoration.** Pick a signature element and let supporting details stay quiet.\n4. **Tokens must explain themselves.** A palette, type scale, spacing rhythm, or motion curve should map to the product's purpose, not to a fashionable preset.\n5. **Remove ornamental numbering.** Avoid `01 / 02 / 03`, fake process markers, and section chrome unless the content is genuinely sequential.\n6. **Respect affordance before novelty.** Distinctive design still needs clear hierarchy, visible focus, legible contrast, and predictable interaction targets.\n7. **Critique the category default, then deviate.** Name the common visual trope for the product category and choose what to keep, bend, or reject.\n8. **Make restraint visible.** If every element competes for attention, the design has no focal point.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Common AI-Default Smells\n\n- Generic cream background, editorial serif headline, terracotta accent, and soft card shadows without a brief-specific reason.\n- Near-black page with one acid accent and oversized geometric gradients as the only identity.\n- Hairline-heavy broadsheet layout where the content has no editorial or archival premise.\n- Repeated glassmorphism, blur, glow, or mesh gradients used as decoration rather than structure.\n- Motion on many small parts instead of one choreographed moment.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Child Usage\n\n- `interface` uses this reference during direction critique.\n- `foundations` uses it to test whether tokens are purposeful.\n- `motion` uses it to avoid scattered animation.\n- `audit` uses it as slop-detection vocabulary.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":60,"totalLines":60,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/anti_slop_principles.md","time":{"start":1782532404706,"end":1782532404710}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0c58cc7090c2c656016a3f49347ecc81918cbcfd0c0d0cb231"}},"id":"prt_f0735f59f001AuQ4mmPdTIZnxr","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","messageID":"msg_f0735b56d001CqC8DrAS2yUPOC"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1782532405154,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","part":{"id":"prt_f0735f79f001AW8husvdJx0rvT","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"e71ed84a96990e75b9a129ea446b8dd65bdb4226","messageID":"msg_f0735b56d001CqC8DrAS2yUPOC","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":127077,"input":4345,"output":262,"reasoning":102,"cache":{"write":0,"read":122368}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1782532407671,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","part":{"id":"prt_f073601760013t4yiOV18sTbBL","messageID":"msg_f0735f9390015P0CZVf1zX7dDY","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","snapshot":"e71ed84a96990e75b9a129ea446b8dd65bdb4226","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1782532424630,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","part":{"id":"prt_f073611de001Z4F9I0ksOIrxq2","messageID":"msg_f0735f9390015P0CZVf1zX7dDY","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","type":"text","text":"The 014 benchmark artifact present in this workspace is for `design-interface`, not `design-motion`; it reports D5 100/100 but aggregate 70/100. I’ll treat the user-provided “motion equals 100 of 100” as an unverified claimed input and record the local evidence contrast in the lineage.","time":{"start":1782532411870,"end":1782532424629},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_055e858694711a0b016a3f493bc308819194a660e1fc7169af","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532424695,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_8req9JjubUhEos0Ywfmg6QbJ","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/references/animation_decision_framework.md","offset":1,"limit":260},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/references/animation_decision_framework.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Animation Decision Framework\n3: description: The restraint gate that decides whether an interaction animates at all, keyed to how often the user sees it and to the register motion-budget dial.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"should this animate\"\n6:   - \"animation decision\"\n7:   - \"motion restraint gate\"\n8:   - \"animation frequency\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: implementation\n11: version: 1.0.0.0\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Animation Decision Framework\n15: \n16: The first motion question is not which easing or how long. It is whether this should animate at all. Frequency decides. An action a user triggers a hundred times a day is never animated. An action they trigger once is where delight can live. This gate is the strongest lever against motion slop, because most over-animated interfaces fail here, not at the timing scale.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n21: \n22: ### Purpose\n23: \n24: Decide whether an interaction earns motion before any timing, easing or material is chosen. This reference owns the restraint gate. Timing, easing and material live in `motion_strategy.md`, and this gate runs before them. If the gate says do not animate, no later choice matters.\n25: \n26: ### When to Use\n27: \n28: - Deciding whether a new interaction gets motion or stays instant.\n29: - Reviewing an interface that feels busy, laggy or over-animated.\n30: - Resolving a request to \"add animation everywhere\" against the register.\n31: - Setting the motion budget for a surface before choreography starts.\n32: \n33: ---\n34: \n35: ## 2. THE FREQUENCY GATE\n36: \n37: How often a user sees an animation decides whether it should exist. The more often an action repeats, the more a delay costs and the faster motion turns from polish into friction.\n38: \n39: | Frequency | Examples | Decision |\n40: | --- | --- | --- |\n41: | 100+ times per day | command palette toggle, keyboard shortcuts, frequent navigation | No animation. Ever. |\n42: | Tens of times per day | hover effects, list navigation, repeated toggles | Remove or reduce hard. |\n43: | Occasional | modals, drawers, toasts | Standard state transition. |\n44: | Rare or first time | onboarding, first success, celebration, empty state | Delight is allowed here. |\n45: \n46: A high-frequency action with motion feels slow even when the duration is short, because the user is waiting on the same delay over and over. Removing the animation makes the interface feel faster without changing a single load time.\n47: \n48: ---\n49: \n50: ## 3. THE KEYBOARD RULE\n51: \n52: Never animate keyboard-initiated actions. A keyboard shortcut exists so a power user can move at speed. Animation on a keyboard action is a delay inserted exactly where the user asked for none. These actions repeat hundreds of times a day, so the cost compounds.\n53: \n54: The clearest example is a command palette with no open or close animation. It appears instantly because it is used constantly. That is the correct experience, not a missing detail.\n55: \n56: Apply the rule to anything a keystroke drives:\n57: - Command palette and quick-switcher open and close.\n58: - Shortcut-driven panel and sidebar toggles.\n59: - Keyboard list and menu navigation.\n60: - Any action whose primary path is a keystroke, even when a click can also trigger it.\n61: \n62: If a click-driven version of the same control wants a small transition, keep the keyboard path instant and let the pointer path carry the motion.\n63: \n64: ---\n65: \n66: ## 4. PURPOSE TEST\n67: \n68: If the gate allows motion, the animation still needs one reason to exist. Name it before specifying anything. A valid purpose is one of:\n69: \n70: - **Feedback.** A press scales down to confirm the interface heard the user.\n71: - **Spatial continuity.** A toast enters and leaves from the same edge so a swipe to dismiss feels obvious.\n72: - **State indication.** A control morphs to show it changed state.\n73: - **Orientation.** A transition shows where a panel came from or went to.\n74: - **Preventing a jarring change.** An element that would otherwise pop in or out gets a short transition so the change does not read as broken.\n75: - **Explanation.** A marketing or onboarding moment shows how something works.\n76: \n77: If the only reason is that it looks cool and the user will see it often, do not animate. Looks-cool is a valid reason exactly once, in the rare or first-time tier, never in the high-frequency tiers.\n78: \n79: ---\n80: \n81: ## 5. REGISTER COUPLING\n82: \n83: This gate reads the motion-budget dial set by the Brand-vs-Product register in `../shared/register.md`. The register decides the ceiling, this gate decides each case under it.\n84: \n85: - **Product surface.** App UI, admin, dashboards, tools, settings and forms. Motion conveys feedback, reveal, loading and view changes through short state transitions. No page-load choreography. Most interactions on a Product surface sit in the high-frequency or tens-per-day tiers, so the gate trims aggressively and the default answer leans toward less motion.\n86: - **Brand surface.** Marketing pages, landing pages, campaigns and portfolios. Motion is voice, so one well-rehearsed entrance is allowed and scroll motion is reserved for a moment that earns it. A Brand surface is seen less often per user, which is what makes a single choreographed moment affordable. It is still one moment, not motion on every section.\n87: \n88: When a surface is unlabeled and internal, treat it as Product and let the gate trim. Reach for the Brand allowance only when the surface is clearly the thing being sold.\n89: \n90: ---\n91: \n92: ## 6. APPLYING THE GATE\n93: \n94: Run the gate in order and stop at the first no.\n95: \n96: 1. **Frequency.** How often does the user see this? At 100-plus per day the answer is no. In the tens per day, cut it or reduce it hard.\n97: 2. **Input.** Is a keystroke the primary trigger? If yes, keep it instant.\n98: 3. **Purpose.** Name the one reason. If the reason is looks-cool and the tier is not rare or first-time, the answer is no.\n99: 4. **Register.** Confirm the choice fits the motion-budget dial for the surface. A Product surface does not get a Brand entrance just because the gate allowed a transition.\n100: \n101: A motion choice that survives all four steps is worth choreographing. Hand it to `motion_strategy.md` for timing, easing and material. A choice that fails any step ships as an instant state change, which is the right outcome, not a downgrade.\n102: \n103: ### Worked Calls\n104: \n105: - **Command palette toggle.** 100-plus per day, keyboard-driven. No animation. Instant open and close.\n106: - **Primary button press.** Occasional to frequent, but feedback is the purpose and the motion is local and sub-`150ms`. Animate the press, keep it tiny.\n107: - **Settings drawer.** Occasional, orientation is the purpose, pointer-driven. Standard state transition.\n108: - **Onboarding success.** First-time, delight is allowed. Choreograph one moment.\n109: - **Row hover on a dense data table used all day.** Tens per day. Reduce to a near-instant color or background change, no movement, so it never slows a scanning power user.\n\n(End of file - total 109 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Animation Decision Framework\ndescription: The restraint gate that decides whether an interaction animates at all, keyed to how often the user sees it and to the register motion-budget dial.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"should this animate\"\n  - \"animation decision\"\n  - \"motion restraint gate\"\n  - \"animation frequency\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Animation Decision Framework\n\nThe first motion question is not which easing or how long. It is whether this should animate at all. Frequency decides. An action a user triggers a hundred times a day is never animated. An action they trigger once is where delight can live. This gate is the strongest lever against motion slop, because most over-animated interfaces fail here, not at the timing scale.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/references/animation_decision_framework.md","text":"---\ntitle: Animation Decision Framework\ndescription: The restraint gate that decides whether an interaction animates at all, keyed to how often the user sees it and to the register motion-budget dial.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"should this animate\"\n  - \"animation decision\"\n  - \"motion restraint gate\"\n  - \"animation frequency\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Animation Decision Framework\n\nThe first motion question is not which easing or how long. It is whether this should animate at all. Frequency decides. An action a user triggers a hundred times a day is never animated. An action they trigger once is where delight can live. This gate is the strongest lever against motion slop, because most over-animated interfaces fail here, not at the timing scale.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nDecide whether an interaction earns motion before any timing, easing or material is chosen. This reference owns the restraint gate. Timing, easing and material live in `motion_strategy.md`, and this gate runs before them. If the gate says do not animate, no later choice matters.\n\n### When to Use\n\n- Deciding whether a new interaction gets motion or stays instant.\n- Reviewing an interface that feels busy, laggy or over-animated.\n- Resolving a request to \"add animation everywhere\" against the register.\n- Setting the motion budget for a surface before choreography starts.\n\n---\n\n## 2. THE FREQUENCY GATE\n\nHow often a user sees an animation decides whether it should exist. The more often an action repeats, the more a delay costs and the faster motion turns from polish into friction.\n\n| Frequency | Examples | Decision |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| 100+ times per day | command palette toggle, keyboard shortcuts, frequent navigation | No animation. Ever. |\n| Tens of times per day | hover effects, list navigation, repeated toggles | Remove or reduce hard. |\n| Occasional | modals, drawers, toasts | Standard state transition. |\n| Rare or first time | onboarding, first success, celebration, empty state | Delight is allowed here. |\n\nA high-frequency action with motion feels slow even when the duration is short, because the user is waiting on the same delay over and over. Removing the animation makes the interface feel faster without changing a single load time.\n\n---\n\n## 3. THE KEYBOARD RULE\n\nNever animate keyboard-initiated actions. A keyboard shortcut exists so a power user can move at speed. Animation on a keyboard action is a delay inserted exactly where the user asked for none. These actions repeat hundreds of times a day, so the cost compounds.\n\nThe clearest example is a command palette with no open or close animation. It appears instantly because it is used constantly. That is the correct experience, not a missing detail.\n\nApply the rule to anything a keystroke drives:\n- Command palette and quick-switcher open and close.\n- Shortcut-driven panel and sidebar toggles.\n- Keyboard list and menu navigation.\n- Any action whose primary path is a keystroke, even when a click can also trigger it.\n\nIf a click-driven version of the same control wants a small transition, keep the keyboard path instant and let the pointer path carry the motion.\n\n---\n\n## 4. PURPOSE TEST\n\nIf the gate allows motion, the animation still needs one reason to exist. Name it before specifying anything. A valid purpose is one of:\n\n- **Feedback.** A press scales down to confirm the interface heard the user.\n- **Spatial continuity.** A toast enters and leaves from the same edge so a swipe to dismiss feels obvious.\n- **State indication.** A control morphs to show it changed state.\n- **Orientation.** A transition shows where a panel came from or went to.\n- **Preventing a jarring change.** An element that would otherwise pop in or out gets a short transition so the change does not read as broken.\n- **Explanation.** A marketing or onboarding moment shows how something works.\n\nIf the only reason is that it looks cool and the user will see it often, do not animate. Looks-cool is a valid reason exactly once, in the rare or first-time tier, never in the high-frequency tiers.\n\n---\n\n## 5. REGISTER COUPLING\n\nThis gate reads the motion-budget dial set by the Brand-vs-Product register in `../shared/register.md`. The register decides the ceiling, this gate decides each case under it.\n\n- **Product surface.** App UI, admin, dashboards, tools, settings and forms. Motion conveys feedback, reveal, loading and view changes through short state transitions. No page-load choreography. Most interactions on a Product surface sit in the high-frequency or tens-per-day tiers, so the gate trims aggressively and the default answer leans toward less motion.\n- **Brand surface.** Marketing pages, landing pages, campaigns and portfolios. Motion is voice, so one well-rehearsed entrance is allowed and scroll motion is reserved for a moment that earns it. A Brand surface is seen less often per user, which is what makes a single choreographed moment affordable. It is still one moment, not motion on every section.\n\nWhen a surface is unlabeled and internal, treat it as Product and let the gate trim. Reach for the Brand allowance only when the surface is clearly the thing being sold.\n\n---\n\n## 6. APPLYING THE GATE\n\nRun the gate in order and stop at the first no.\n\n1. **Frequency.** How often does the user see this? At 100-plus per day the answer is no. In the tens per day, cut it or reduce it hard.\n2. **Input.** Is a keystroke the primary trigger? If yes, keep it instant.\n3. **Purpose.** Name the one reason. If the reason is looks-cool and the tier is not rare or first-time, the answer is no.\n4. **Register.** Confirm the choice fits the motion-budget dial for the surface. A Product surface does not get a Brand entrance just because the gate allowed a transition.\n\nA motion choice that survives all four steps is worth choreographing. Hand it to `motion_strategy.md` for timing, easing and material. A choice that fails any step ships as an instant state change, which is the right outcome, not a downgrade.\n\n### Worked Calls\n\n- **Command palette toggle.** 100-plus per day, keyboard-driven. No animation. Instant open and close.\n- **Primary button press.** Occasional to frequent, but feedback is the purpose and the motion is local and sub-`150ms`. Animate the press, keep it tiny.\n- **Settings drawer.** Occasional, orientation is the purpose, pointer-driven. Standard state transition.\n- **Onboarding success.** First-time, delight is allowed. Choreograph one moment.\n- **Row hover on a dense data table used all day.** Tens per day. Reduce to a near-instant color or background change, no movement, so it never slows a scanning power user.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":109,"totalLines":109,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/references/animation_decision_framework.md","time":{"start":1782532424685,"end":1782532424693}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_055e858694711a0b016a3f494896308191b2605ff4570dcafa"}},"id":"prt_f073643b8001NxuBs1T9yiVgcB","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","messageID":"msg_f0735f9390015P0CZVf1zX7dDY"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532424744,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_zHCX8XBytxgUqd7w4scRJSvU","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/references/motion_strategy.md","offset":1,"limit":280},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/references/motion_strategy.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Motion Strategy\n3: description: Purpose, timing, easing, staging, animation principles, and material choice for interface motion.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"motion strategy\"\n6:   - \"animation timing\"\n7:   - \"motion easing\"\n8:   - \"motion materials\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: implementation\n11: version: 1.0.0.0\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Motion Strategy\n15: \n16: Motion must communicate. Before choosing a library or property, name the job: feedback, orientation, focus, continuity, perceived performance, or earned delight.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n21: \n22: ### Purpose\n23: \n24: Decide why an interface element moves before deciding how. This reference covers the motion budget, timing scale, easing, staging, material choice, and the verification checks that keep animation purposeful rather than decorative.\n25: \n26: ### When to Use\n27: \n28: - Choosing whether a state change deserves motion at all.\n29: - Setting duration and easing for feedback, transitions, or an earned hero moment.\n30: - Picking the animation material (transform/opacity, blur, clip-path, FLIP) for a given effect.\n31: - Verifying that motion supports the primary content instead of competing with it.\n32: \n33: ---\n34: \n35: ## 2. Motion Budget\n36: \n37: | Layer | Use when | Rule |\n38: | --- | --- | --- |\n39: | Hero moment | One memorable brand or landing-page event earns choreography | One moment, not every section. |\n40: | Feedback | Button press, toggle, validation, save, copy, drag | Fast and local. |\n41: | Transition | Modal, drawer, tab, route, accordion, list changes | Clarifies where state came from or went. |\n42: | Delight | Success, milestone, empty state, hidden discovery | Brief, contextual, skippable, never blocking. |\n43: \n44: If motion does not improve clarity or feeling at one of these layers, remove it.\n45: \n46: ## 3. Timing\n47: \n48: | Duration | Use case |\n49: | --- | --- |\n50: | `100-150ms` | press, hover, tap, tiny feedback |\n51: | `200-300ms` | toggle, dropdown, tooltip, tab change |\n52: | `300-500ms` | modal, drawer, accordion, layout transition |\n53: | `500-800ms` | one earned entrance or brand choreography |\n54: \n55: This is the 100/300/500 rule: roughly 100ms for instant feedback, 300ms for state changes, 500ms for layout changes, and timing matters more than easing for whether motion feels right. Exit animations should usually run at about 75 percent of the entrance duration. User-initiated feedback over `300ms` feels laggy. Anything under about `80ms` reads as effectively instant, because perception buffers input for roughly that long; keep the fastest feedback tier near its `100-150ms` floor so micro-interactions land at the edge of that instant window.\n56: \n57: ## 4. Easing\n58: \n59: Use deceleration for arrivals:\n60: \n61: ```css\n62: --ease-out-quart: cubic-bezier(0.25, 1, 0.5, 1);\n63: --ease-out-quint: cubic-bezier(0.22, 1, 0.36, 1);\n64: --ease-out-expo: cubic-bezier(0.16, 1, 0.3, 1);\n65: ```\n66: \n67: Use ease-in for exits and spring only when overshoot-and-settle is the actual desired physical feel. Avoid bounce or elastic defaults.\n68: \n69: Reserve `linear` for determinate progress bars and similar progress indicators; never use it for movement. Linear motion reads as mechanical, so transforms and position changes should use a deceleration or ease-in curve, not `linear`.\n70: \n71: ## 5. Staging\n72: \n73: - Animate one focal point prominently at a time.\n74: - Dim modal backgrounds to direct focus.\n75: - Coordinate z-index and layer hierarchy before animating overlays.\n76: - Stagger lists only when they are actual related siblings. Cap total delay; reduce per-item delay when the list is long.\n77: \n78: ## 6. Motion Materials\n79: \n80: Transform and opacity are reliable defaults, but not the whole palette.\n81: \n82: | Material | Use for | Constraint |\n83: | --- | --- | --- |\n84: | Transform/opacity | movement, press, simple reveals, list choreography | preferred default |\n85: | Blur/filter/backdrop | focus pulls, lens, glass, softened entrances | small, bounded, verified smooth |\n86: | Clip-path/masks | wipes, editorial reveals, product transitions | avoid large continuous masks |\n87: | Shadow/glow/color | active state, affordance, warmth | local UI only; avoid page-wide effects |\n88: | FLIP/grid-row | layout-like transitions | measure once, animate transform or bounded row expansion |\n89: \n90: ## 7. Verification\n91: \n92: Check:\n93: - Purpose named.\n94: - Timing and easing match the state.\n95: - Similar elements use consistent timing.\n96: - Reduced-motion alternative exists.\n97: - Motion does not compete with the primary content.\n98: - Interaction remains usable during and after motion.\n\n(End of file - total 98 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Motion Strategy\ndescription: Purpose, timing, easing, staging, animation principles, and material choice for interface motion.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"motion strategy\"\n  - \"animation timing\"\n  - \"motion easing\"\n  - \"motion materials\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Motion Strategy\n\nMotion must communicate. Before choosing a library or property, name the job: feedback, orientation, focus, continuity, perceived performance, or earned delight.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/references/motion_strategy.md","text":"---\ntitle: Motion Strategy\ndescription: Purpose, timing, easing, staging, animation principles, and material choice for interface motion.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"motion strategy\"\n  - \"animation timing\"\n  - \"motion easing\"\n  - \"motion materials\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Motion Strategy\n\nMotion must communicate. Before choosing a library or property, name the job: feedback, orientation, focus, continuity, perceived performance, or earned delight.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nDecide why an interface element moves before deciding how. This reference covers the motion budget, timing scale, easing, staging, material choice, and the verification checks that keep animation purposeful rather than decorative.\n\n### When to Use\n\n- Choosing whether a state change deserves motion at all.\n- Setting duration and easing for feedback, transitions, or an earned hero moment.\n- Picking the animation material (transform/opacity, blur, clip-path, FLIP) for a given effect.\n- Verifying that motion supports the primary content instead of competing with it.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Motion Budget\n\n| Layer | Use when | Rule |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Hero moment | One memorable brand or landing-page event earns choreography | One moment, not every section. |\n| Feedback | Button press, toggle, validation, save, copy, drag | Fast and local. |\n| Transition | Modal, drawer, tab, route, accordion, list changes | Clarifies where state came from or went. |\n| Delight | Success, milestone, empty state, hidden discovery | Brief, contextual, skippable, never blocking. |\n\nIf motion does not improve clarity or feeling at one of these layers, remove it.\n\n## 3. Timing\n\n| Duration | Use case |\n| --- | --- |\n| `100-150ms` | press, hover, tap, tiny feedback |\n| `200-300ms` | toggle, dropdown, tooltip, tab change |\n| `300-500ms` | modal, drawer, accordion, layout transition |\n| `500-800ms` | one earned entrance or brand choreography |\n\nThis is the 100/300/500 rule: roughly 100ms for instant feedback, 300ms for state changes, 500ms for layout changes, and timing matters more than easing for whether motion feels right. Exit animations should usually run at about 75 percent of the entrance duration. User-initiated feedback over `300ms` feels laggy. Anything under about `80ms` reads as effectively instant, because perception buffers input for roughly that long; keep the fastest feedback tier near its `100-150ms` floor so micro-interactions land at the edge of that instant window.\n\n## 4. Easing\n\nUse deceleration for arrivals:\n\n```css\n--ease-out-quart: cubic-bezier(0.25, 1, 0.5, 1);\n--ease-out-quint: cubic-bezier(0.22, 1, 0.36, 1);\n--ease-out-expo: cubic-bezier(0.16, 1, 0.3, 1);\n```\n\nUse ease-in for exits and spring only when overshoot-and-settle is the actual desired physical feel. Avoid bounce or elastic defaults.\n\nReserve `linear` for determinate progress bars and similar progress indicators; never use it for movement. Linear motion reads as mechanical, so transforms and position changes should use a deceleration or ease-in curve, not `linear`.\n\n## 5. Staging\n\n- Animate one focal point prominently at a time.\n- Dim modal backgrounds to direct focus.\n- Coordinate z-index and layer hierarchy before animating overlays.\n- Stagger lists only when they are actual related siblings. Cap total delay; reduce per-item delay when the list is long.\n\n## 6. Motion Materials\n\nTransform and opacity are reliable defaults, but not the whole palette.\n\n| Material | Use for | Constraint |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Transform/opacity | movement, press, simple reveals, list choreography | preferred default |\n| Blur/filter/backdrop | focus pulls, lens, glass, softened entrances | small, bounded, verified smooth |\n| Clip-path/masks | wipes, editorial reveals, product transitions | avoid large continuous masks |\n| Shadow/glow/color | active state, affordance, warmth | local UI only; avoid page-wide effects |\n| FLIP/grid-row | layout-like transitions | measure once, animate transform or bounded row expansion |\n\n## 7. Verification\n\nCheck:\n- Purpose named.\n- Timing and easing match the state.\n- Similar elements use consistent timing.\n- Reduced-motion alternative exists.\n- Motion does not compete with the primary content.\n- Interaction remains usable during and after motion.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":98,"totalLines":98,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/references/motion_strategy.md","time":{"start":1782532424738,"end":1782532424743}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_055e858694711a0b016a3f49489640819181de5bff6adb0ba9"}},"id":"prt_f07364406001o07VQzj3boBUX1","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","messageID":"msg_f0735f9390015P0CZVf1zX7dDY"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532424782,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_Kw46MnV7XXlnlvNuMizift7c","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/references/micro_interactions.md","offset":1,"limit":260},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/references/micro_interactions.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Micro-Interactions And Delight\n3: description: Interaction feedback, loading states, gestures, earned delight, copy boundaries, and morphing-icon rules.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"micro interactions\"\n6:   - \"interaction feedback\"\n7:   - \"delight moments\"\n8:   - \"morphing icons\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: implementation\n11: version: 1.0.0.0\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Micro-Interactions And Delight\n15: \n16: Micro-interactions confirm that an action happened, explain state, and make the interface feel responsive. Delight is only useful when the moment earns it.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n21: \n22: ### Purpose\n23: \n24: Design the small, local feedback that makes an interface feel alive and trustworthy, and decide when a moment earns added delight. This reference covers feedback patterns, loading states, gestures, delight boundaries, morphing-icon rules, and the implementation handoff snippet.\n25: \n26: ### When to Use\n27: \n28: - Specifying hover, active, focus, loading, success, or error feedback for a control.\n29: - Choosing loading and waiting treatments that preserve layout and set expectations.\n30: - Deciding whether a success, milestone, or recovery moment earns delight.\n31: - Defining morphing-icon behavior or handing motion intent to implementation.\n32: \n33: ---\n34: \n35: ## 2. Feedback Patterns\n36: \n37: | State | Motion pattern | Notes |\n38: | --- | --- | --- |\n39: | Hover | small lift, color shift, shadow, icon cue | Must not be the only disclosure path. A lift such as `scale(1.05)` is a hover affordance, not a press. |\n40: | Active | quick scale down then up, depressed shadow | Required, not optional: every interactive control needs an active/pressed state. Press scale stays in `0.95-1.0` (commonly `0.96`); never below `0.95`. |\n41: | Focus | visible ring or path highlight | Keyboard parity required. |\n42: | Loading | skeleton, progress, optimistic state | Explain what is happening when waits are long. |\n43: | Success | checkmark, gentle pulse, brief celebration | Reserve confetti for real milestones. |\n44: | Error | local shake or color/icon shift | Do not punish; pair with clear copy. |\n45: \n46: Interactive controls REQUIRE an active/pressed state; a hover-only control fails physics expectations. Press feedback scales down into the `0.95-1.0` range (`0.96` is a good default) and never below `0.95`, which reads as exaggerated. The `1.05` value belongs to a hover lift, not a press.\n47: \n48: ### Animation Mechanism\n49: \n50: - Use CSS transitions for interactive state changes (hover, active, focus, toggle). They can be interrupted mid-animation, so a user who reverses an action gets an immediate response instead of waiting for a keyframe sequence to finish.\n51: - Reserve keyframes (`@keyframes`, one-shot Motion sequences) for staged sequences that run once, such as a success flourish or an entrance.\n52: - For springs on most UI and icon motion, set `bounce: 0` (for example `transition: { type: \"spring\", duration: 0.3, bounce: 0 }`). Keep overshoot only when an element should physically settle; default icon and control springs should not bounce.\n53: \n54: ## 3. Loading And Waiting\n55: \n56: - Skeletons preserve layout and reduce perceived wait.\n57: - Progress bars should be determinate when progress is knowable.\n58: - Loading copy must be product-specific: `Syncing your team's changes...`, not generic jokes.\n59: - For waits above a few seconds, set expectations or provide cancel/escape.\n60: \n61: ## 4. Gestures\n62: \n63: - Drag states need lift, target feedback, and rollback/undo when meaningful.\n64: - Swipe actions need thresholds and visible alternatives.\n65: - Touch interactions need 44 by 44 pixel targets and spacing.\n66: - Gesture-only actions need accessible alternatives.\n67: \n68: ## 5. Delight Boundaries\n69: \n70: Delight belongs at success, first-time action, empty state, milestone, or error recovery. It should be quick, appropriate, and optional. If users notice the delight more than their task, it has gone too far.\n71: \n72: Never:\n73: - Delay the core action for delight.\n74: - Use humor in critical errors.\n75: - Add celebration to routine low-value actions.\n76: - Play sound without respecting system settings and mute controls.\n77: - Repeat the same flourish until it becomes noise.\n78: \n79: ## 6. Morphing Icons\n80: \n81: Use morphing icons only when transformation communicates state continuity, such as menu to close, plus to cross, arrow direction, or play to pause.\n82: \n83: Rules distilled from the corpus:\n84: - Every icon in a morphing set uses exactly three SVG lines.\n85: - Icons needing fewer lines collapse extras to invisible center points.\n86: - All icons share one viewBox, commonly `14x14`.\n87: - Rotational variants share base lines and a group.\n88: - Grouped rotations may animate; unrelated rotations jump instantly.\n89: - Lines use `strokeLinecap=\"round\"`.\n90: - Decorative icon SVGs are `aria-hidden=\"true\"`; the control carries the accessible name.\n91: - Reduced motion sets transition duration to zero or swaps instantly.\n92: \n93: ## 7. Handoff Snippet\n94: \n95: When handing to implementation, include:\n96: \n97: ```text\n98: Motion purpose: feedback / orientation / focus / continuity / delight\n99: Trigger state: default -> hover -> active -> loading -> success/error\n100: Timing: <duration> and <easing/spring>\n101: Properties: transform/opacity/etc.\n102: Reduced motion: <alternate behavior>\n103: Performance risk: <none / bounded paint / FLIP / scroll>\n104: ```\n\n(End of file - total 104 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Micro-Interactions And Delight\ndescription: Interaction feedback, loading states, gestures, earned delight, copy boundaries, and morphing-icon rules.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"micro interactions\"\n  - \"interaction feedback\"\n  - \"delight moments\"\n  - \"morphing icons\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Micro-Interactions And Delight\n\nMicro-interactions confirm that an action happened, explain state, and make the interface feel responsive. Delight is only useful when the moment earns it.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/references/micro_interactions.md","text":"---\ntitle: Micro-Interactions And Delight\ndescription: Interaction feedback, loading states, gestures, earned delight, copy boundaries, and morphing-icon rules.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"micro interactions\"\n  - \"interaction feedback\"\n  - \"delight moments\"\n  - \"morphing icons\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Micro-Interactions And Delight\n\nMicro-interactions confirm that an action happened, explain state, and make the interface feel responsive. Delight is only useful when the moment earns it.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nDesign the small, local feedback that makes an interface feel alive and trustworthy, and decide when a moment earns added delight. This reference covers feedback patterns, loading states, gestures, delight boundaries, morphing-icon rules, and the implementation handoff snippet.\n\n### When to Use\n\n- Specifying hover, active, focus, loading, success, or error feedback for a control.\n- Choosing loading and waiting treatments that preserve layout and set expectations.\n- Deciding whether a success, milestone, or recovery moment earns delight.\n- Defining morphing-icon behavior or handing motion intent to implementation.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Feedback Patterns\n\n| State | Motion pattern | Notes |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Hover | small lift, color shift, shadow, icon cue | Must not be the only disclosure path. A lift such as `scale(1.05)` is a hover affordance, not a press. |\n| Active | quick scale down then up, depressed shadow | Required, not optional: every interactive control needs an active/pressed state. Press scale stays in `0.95-1.0` (commonly `0.96`); never below `0.95`. |\n| Focus | visible ring or path highlight | Keyboard parity required. |\n| Loading | skeleton, progress, optimistic state | Explain what is happening when waits are long. |\n| Success | checkmark, gentle pulse, brief celebration | Reserve confetti for real milestones. |\n| Error | local shake or color/icon shift | Do not punish; pair with clear copy. |\n\nInteractive controls REQUIRE an active/pressed state; a hover-only control fails physics expectations. Press feedback scales down into the `0.95-1.0` range (`0.96` is a good default) and never below `0.95`, which reads as exaggerated. The `1.05` value belongs to a hover lift, not a press.\n\n### Animation Mechanism\n\n- Use CSS transitions for interactive state changes (hover, active, focus, toggle). They can be interrupted mid-animation, so a user who reverses an action gets an immediate response instead of waiting for a keyframe sequence to finish.\n- Reserve keyframes (`@keyframes`, one-shot Motion sequences) for staged sequences that run once, such as a success flourish or an entrance.\n- For springs on most UI and icon motion, set `bounce: 0` (for example `transition: { type: \"spring\", duration: 0.3, bounce: 0 }`). Keep overshoot only when an element should physically settle; default icon and control springs should not bounce.\n\n## 3. Loading And Waiting\n\n- Skeletons preserve layout and reduce perceived wait.\n- Progress bars should be determinate when progress is knowable.\n- Loading copy must be product-specific: `Syncing your team's changes...`, not generic jokes.\n- For waits above a few seconds, set expectations or provide cancel/escape.\n\n## 4. Gestures\n\n- Drag states need lift, target feedback, and rollback/undo when meaningful.\n- Swipe actions need thresholds and visible alternatives.\n- Touch interactions need 44 by 44 pixel targets and spacing.\n- Gesture-only actions need accessible alternatives.\n\n## 5. Delight Boundaries\n\nDelight belongs at success, first-time action, empty state, milestone, or error recovery. It should be quick, appropriate, and optional. If users notice the delight more than their task, it has gone too far.\n\nNever:\n- Delay the core action for delight.\n- Use humor in critical errors.\n- Add celebration to routine low-value actions.\n- Play sound without respecting system settings and mute controls.\n- Repeat the same flourish until it becomes noise.\n\n## 6. Morphing Icons\n\nUse morphing icons only when transformation communicates state continuity, such as menu to close, plus to cross, arrow direction, or play to pause.\n\nRules distilled from the corpus:\n- Every icon in a morphing set uses exactly three SVG lines.\n- Icons needing fewer lines collapse extras to invisible center points.\n- All icons share one viewBox, commonly `14x14`.\n- Rotational variants share base lines and a group.\n- Grouped rotations may animate; unrelated rotations jump instantly.\n- Lines use `strokeLinecap=\"round\"`.\n- Decorative icon SVGs are `aria-hidden=\"true\"`; the control carries the accessible name.\n- Reduced motion sets transition duration to zero or swaps instantly.\n\n## 7. Handoff Snippet\n\nWhen handing to implementation, include:\n\n```text\nMotion purpose: feedback / orientation / focus / continuity / delight\nTrigger state: default -> hover -> active -> loading -> success/error\nTiming: <duration> and <easing/spring>\nProperties: transform/opacity/etc.\nReduced motion: <alternate behavior>\nPerformance risk: <none / bounded paint / FLIP / scroll>\n```","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":104,"totalLines":104,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/references/micro_interactions.md","time":{"start":1782532424779,"end":1782532424782}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_055e858694711a0b016a3f4948964881918542dfc22443ac4a"}},"id":"prt_f07364424001EHeJ45gLzjyIY4","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","messageID":"msg_f0735f9390015P0CZVf1zX7dDY"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532424858,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_MLYqzjivcn9Z0tT1mc32Inim","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/references/animate_presence_patterns.md","offset":1,"limit":260},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/references/animate_presence_patterns.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: AnimatePresence Patterns\n3: description: Motion/Framer Motion and AnimatePresence rules for exits, keys, modes, presence hooks, nested exits, and list transitions.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"AnimatePresence patterns\"\n6:   - \"exit animation\"\n7:   - \"motion react\"\n8:   - \"presence hooks\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: implementation\n11: version: 1.0.0.0\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # AnimatePresence Patterns\n15: \n16: Use `AnimatePresence` when conditional React elements need exit animations after they leave render state. Missing wrappers, unstable keys, and mismatched modes are the common failure modes.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n21: \n22: ### Purpose\n23: \n24: Apply Motion/Framer Motion `AnimatePresence` correctly so conditional elements animate out instead of disappearing. This reference covers exit rules, presence modes, presence hooks, nested exits, list transitions, and the format for reporting audit findings.\n25: \n26: ### When to Use\n27: \n28: - Adding exit animations to conditionally rendered React elements.\n29: - Choosing a presence mode (`sync`, `wait`, `popLayout`) for overlays, route changes, or lists.\n30: - Coordinating presence hooks, async cleanup, or nested exit propagation.\n31: - Auditing existing motion code for missing wrappers, unstable keys, or mismatched modes.\n32: \n33: ---\n34: \n35: ## 2. Exit Rules\n36: \n37: | Rule | Pass condition |\n38: | --- | --- |\n39: | Conditional wrapper | Conditional `motion.*` elements with `exit` are inside `AnimatePresence`. |\n40: | Exit prop | Every element expected to animate out has an `exit` prop. |\n41: | Stable key | Dynamic items use data IDs, not array indexes. |\n42: | Symmetry | Exit mirrors initial direction unless a different departure is intentional. |\n43: | No first-render enter | Elements already present on mount use `initial={false}` on `AnimatePresence` so the enter animation does not play on page load. |\n44: \n45: Set `initial={false}` on `AnimatePresence` when its child is rendered in its default state on first mount; this suppresses the first-render enter animation. Verify it does not cancel an entrance you actually want on load.\n46: \n47: Example:\n48: \n49: ```tsx\n50: <AnimatePresence>\n51:   {isOpen && (\n52:     <motion.div\n53:       key=\"settings-panel\"\n54:       initial={{ opacity: 0, y: 16 }}\n55:       animate={{ opacity: 1, y: 0 }}\n56:       // Enter: ease-out, arrive fast and settle gently.\n57:       transition={{ duration: 0.22, ease: [0.16, 1, 0.3, 1] }}\n58:       // Exit: own faster ease-in transition (~75% of enter). Do not reuse\n59:       // the ease-out enter curve for exits (violates the ease-in-for-exits rule).\n60:       exit={{ opacity: 0, y: 16, transition: { duration: 0.16, ease: [0.55, 0, 1, 0.45] } }}\n61:     />\n62:   )}\n63: </AnimatePresence>\n64: ```\n65: \n66: The `exit` transition is defined on the `exit` prop itself so it does not inherit the ease-out enter curve. Enter uses ease-out (`[0.16, 1, 0.3, 1]`); exit uses ease-in (`[0.55, 0, 1, 0.45]`) at `0.16s`, about 75 percent of the enter duration, satisfying both the ease-in-for-exits rule and the exits-faster rule.\n67: \n68: ## 3. Modes\n69: \n70: | Mode | Use for | Risk and remedy |\n71: | --- | --- | --- |\n72: | default/sync | simple overlays where enter and exit can overlap | Exiting and entering elements compete for layout. Remedy: position exiting elements `absolute` so they leave the flow, or prefer `popLayout` for lists. |\n73: | `wait` | route/page replacement where old must leave before new enters | Total time doubles; shorten each phase. |\n74: | `popLayout` | list reordering or removal | Requires layout-aware children and stable keys. |\n75: \n76: If `mode=\"wait\"` uses `0.3s` enter and `0.3s` exit, the user perceives about `0.6s`. Reduce each phase when the total must feel fast.\n77: \n78: ## 4. Presence Hooks\n79: \n80: - `useIsPresent` belongs in a child of `AnimatePresence`, not the parent.\n81: - Exiting elements should disable interactions when no longer present.\n82: - If `usePresence` performs async cleanup, call `safeToRemove` after cleanup completes.\n83: \n84: ## 5. Nested Exits\n85: \n86: Nested `AnimatePresence` needs `propagate` when child exits should run as the parent exits. Coordinate parent and child durations; a parent that vanishes before children complete makes exits look broken.\n87: \n88: ## 6. Lists\n89: \n90: - Use item IDs for keys.\n91: - Keep stagger under `50ms` per item and cap total stagger.\n92: - Use `popLayout` when removal changes list geometry.\n93: - Avoid animating every list item on routine resort/filter operations if it slows power users.\n94: \n95: ## 7. Audit Findings Format\n96: \n97: When reviewing implementation, report findings like:\n98: \n99: ```text\n100: components/modal.tsx:42 - [exit-requires-wrapper] Conditional motion.div has exit but is not wrapped in AnimatePresence.\n101: components/list.tsx:88 - [exit-key-required] Animated list uses index key; use item.id to preserve identity.\n102: ```\n\n(End of file - total 102 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: AnimatePresence Patterns\ndescription: Motion/Framer Motion and AnimatePresence rules for exits, keys, modes, presence hooks, nested exits, and list transitions.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"AnimatePresence patterns\"\n  - \"exit animation\"\n  - \"motion react\"\n  - \"presence hooks\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# AnimatePresence Patterns\n\nUse `AnimatePresence` when conditional React elements need exit animations after they leave render state. Missing wrappers, unstable keys, and mismatched modes are the common failure modes.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/references/animate_presence_patterns.md","text":"---\ntitle: AnimatePresence Patterns\ndescription: Motion/Framer Motion and AnimatePresence rules for exits, keys, modes, presence hooks, nested exits, and list transitions.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"AnimatePresence patterns\"\n  - \"exit animation\"\n  - \"motion react\"\n  - \"presence hooks\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# AnimatePresence Patterns\n\nUse `AnimatePresence` when conditional React elements need exit animations after they leave render state. Missing wrappers, unstable keys, and mismatched modes are the common failure modes.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nApply Motion/Framer Motion `AnimatePresence` correctly so conditional elements animate out instead of disappearing. This reference covers exit rules, presence modes, presence hooks, nested exits, list transitions, and the format for reporting audit findings.\n\n### When to Use\n\n- Adding exit animations to conditionally rendered React elements.\n- Choosing a presence mode (`sync`, `wait`, `popLayout`) for overlays, route changes, or lists.\n- Coordinating presence hooks, async cleanup, or nested exit propagation.\n- Auditing existing motion code for missing wrappers, unstable keys, or mismatched modes.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Exit Rules\n\n| Rule | Pass condition |\n| --- | --- |\n| Conditional wrapper | Conditional `motion.*` elements with `exit` are inside `AnimatePresence`. |\n| Exit prop | Every element expected to animate out has an `exit` prop. |\n| Stable key | Dynamic items use data IDs, not array indexes. |\n| Symmetry | Exit mirrors initial direction unless a different departure is intentional. |\n| No first-render enter | Elements already present on mount use `initial={false}` on `AnimatePresence` so the enter animation does not play on page load. |\n\nSet `initial={false}` on `AnimatePresence` when its child is rendered in its default state on first mount; this suppresses the first-render enter animation. Verify it does not cancel an entrance you actually want on load.\n\nExample:\n\n```tsx\n<AnimatePresence>\n  {isOpen && (\n    <motion.div\n      key=\"settings-panel\"\n      initial={{ opacity: 0, y: 16 }}\n      animate={{ opacity: 1, y: 0 }}\n      // Enter: ease-out, arrive fast and settle gently.\n      transition={{ duration: 0.22, ease: [0.16, 1, 0.3, 1] }}\n      // Exit: own faster ease-in transition (~75% of enter). Do not reuse\n      // the ease-out enter curve for exits (violates the ease-in-for-exits rule).\n      exit={{ opacity: 0, y: 16, transition: { duration: 0.16, ease: [0.55, 0, 1, 0.45] } }}\n    />\n  )}\n</AnimatePresence>\n```\n\nThe `exit` transition is defined on the `exit` prop itself so it does not inherit the ease-out enter curve. Enter uses ease-out (`[0.16, 1, 0.3, 1]`); exit uses ease-in (`[0.55, 0, 1, 0.45]`) at `0.16s`, about 75 percent of the enter duration, satisfying both the ease-in-for-exits rule and the exits-faster rule.\n\n## 3. Modes\n\n| Mode | Use for | Risk and remedy |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| default/sync | simple overlays where enter and exit can overlap | Exiting and entering elements compete for layout. Remedy: position exiting elements `absolute` so they leave the flow, or prefer `popLayout` for lists. |\n| `wait` | route/page replacement where old must leave before new enters | Total time doubles; shorten each phase. |\n| `popLayout` | list reordering or removal | Requires layout-aware children and stable keys. |\n\nIf `mode=\"wait\"` uses `0.3s` enter and `0.3s` exit, the user perceives about `0.6s`. Reduce each phase when the total must feel fast.\n\n## 4. Presence Hooks\n\n- `useIsPresent` belongs in a child of `AnimatePresence`, not the parent.\n- Exiting elements should disable interactions when no longer present.\n- If `usePresence` performs async cleanup, call `safeToRemove` after cleanup completes.\n\n## 5. Nested Exits\n\nNested `AnimatePresence` needs `propagate` when child exits should run as the parent exits. Coordinate parent and child durations; a parent that vanishes before children complete makes exits look broken.\n\n## 6. Lists\n\n- Use item IDs for keys.\n- Keep stagger under `50ms` per item and cap total stagger.\n- Use `popLayout` when removal changes list geometry.\n- Avoid animating every list item on routine resort/filter operations if it slows power users.\n\n## 7. Audit Findings Format\n\nWhen reviewing implementation, report findings like:\n\n```text\ncomponents/modal.tsx:42 - [exit-requires-wrapper] Conditional motion.div has exit but is not wrapped in AnimatePresence.\ncomponents/list.tsx:88 - [exit-key-required] Animated list uses index key; use item.id to preserve identity.\n```","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":102,"totalLines":102,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/references/animate_presence_patterns.md","time":{"start":1782532424852,"end":1782532424856}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_055e858694711a0b016a3f4948965081919e69f8e14fb60634"}},"id":"prt_f073644570016gWHp6JHbIGDnJ","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","messageID":"msg_f0735f9390015P0CZVf1zX7dDY"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532424886,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_sdvciz3Pkq8NrSj9GUwUg4Vz","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/references/performance_reduced_motion.md","offset":1,"limit":300},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/references/performance_reduced_motion.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Performance And Reduced Motion\n3: description: Animation performance, compositor safety, FLIP, scroll motion, layers, blur/filter bounds, and reduced-motion alternatives.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"motion performance\"\n6:   - \"reduced motion\"\n7:   - \"animation jank\"\n8:   - \"FLIP animation\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: implementation\n11: version: 1.0.0.0\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Performance And Reduced Motion\n15: \n16: Motion that janks, drains battery, or ignores user preference is not polish. It is a defect.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n21: \n22: ### Purpose\n23: \n24: Keep motion smooth, battery-safe, and respectful of user preference. This reference covers rendering cost, the critical never patterns, the FLIP technique, scroll motion, blur and layer bounds, reduced-motion alternatives, and the checks that confirm performance before claiming it.\n25: \n26: ### When to Use\n27: \n28: - Choosing properties that stay on the compositor and avoid layout thrash.\n29: - Implementing layout-like transitions via FLIP or driving scroll-linked motion safely.\n30: - Bounding blur, filters, and promoted layers to protect memory and frame rate.\n31: - Providing a reduced-motion path that still communicates state, and verifying it.\n32: \n33: ---\n34: \n35: ## 2. Rendering Cost\n36: \n37: | Rendering step | Examples | Guidance |\n38: | --- | --- | --- |\n39: | Composite | `transform`, `opacity` | Default for reliable motion. |\n40: | Paint | color, border, shadow, filter, mask, image | Allowed for small, bounded, short-lived effects. |\n41: | Layout | width, height, top, left, margin, flow changes | Avoid continuous animation; use FLIP or structural alternatives. |\n42: \n43: ## 3. Critical Never Patterns\n44: \n45: - Do not interleave layout reads and writes in the same frame.\n46: - Do not drive animation from `scrollTop`, `scrollY`, or raw scroll events.\n47: - Do not run `requestAnimationFrame` loops without a stop condition.\n48: - Do not mix multiple animation systems inside the same interaction surface.\n49: - Do not add `will-change` everywhere; use it temporarily and surgically, only on compositable properties (`transform`, `opacity`, `filter`), and never `will-change: all`.\n50: - Never use `transition: all`. Name the exact properties instead, for example `transition-property: transform, opacity`. `transition: all` animates unexpected properties and can trigger layout or paint work you never intended.\n51: \n52: ## 4. FLIP Pattern\n53: \n54: For layout-like transitions:\n55: 1. Measure the first geometry.\n56: 2. Apply the layout change.\n57: 3. Measure the last geometry.\n58: 4. Invert with transform.\n59: 5. Play transform back to zero.\n60: \n61: This makes the user perceive layout motion while the animation itself stays compositor-friendly.\n62: \n63: ## 5. Scroll Motion\n64: \n65: - Use IntersectionObserver for visibility and pausing.\n66: - Use Scroll or View Timelines when the platform supports them.\n67: - Unobserve one-shot reveals after they run.\n68: - Avoid default fade-and-rise section reveals across an entire page.\n69: - Pause loops when off-screen.\n70: \n71: ## 6. Blur, Filters, And Layers\n72: \n73: - Keep blur small, typically `<= 8px`, and short-lived.\n74: - Avoid continuous blur on large surfaces.\n75: - Isolate expensive effects with containment when possible.\n76: - Limit promoted layers; too many layers consume memory and can reduce performance.\n77: \n78: ## 7. Reduced Motion\n79: \n80: Reduced motion does not mean no state feedback. Replace movement with instant state changes, opacity shifts, color/focus changes, or static progress cues.\n81: \n82: ```css\n83: @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {\n84:   *, *::before, *::after {\n85:     animation-duration: 0.01ms !important;\n86:     animation-iteration-count: 1 !important;\n87:     transition-duration: 0.01ms !important;\n88:   }\n89: }\n90: ```\n91: \n92: For React motion, use `useReducedMotion()` and swap to `{ duration: 0 }` or a non-motion state.\n93: \n94: ## 8. Verification\n95: \n96: - Test on the lowest target device, not only desktop Chrome.\n97: - Confirm no interaction is blocked during motion.\n98: - Confirm loops pause off-screen.\n99: - Confirm reduced-motion path communicates the same state.\n100: - Measure before claiming performance improved.\n\n(End of file - total 100 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Performance And Reduced Motion\ndescription: Animation performance, compositor safety, FLIP, scroll motion, layers, blur/filter bounds, and reduced-motion alternatives.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"motion performance\"\n  - \"reduced motion\"\n  - \"animation jank\"\n  - \"FLIP animation\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Performance And Reduced Motion\n\nMotion that janks, drains battery, or ignores user preference is not polish. It is a defect.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/references/performance_reduced_motion.md","text":"---\ntitle: Performance And Reduced Motion\ndescription: Animation performance, compositor safety, FLIP, scroll motion, layers, blur/filter bounds, and reduced-motion alternatives.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"motion performance\"\n  - \"reduced motion\"\n  - \"animation jank\"\n  - \"FLIP animation\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Performance And Reduced Motion\n\nMotion that janks, drains battery, or ignores user preference is not polish. It is a defect.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nKeep motion smooth, battery-safe, and respectful of user preference. This reference covers rendering cost, the critical never patterns, the FLIP technique, scroll motion, blur and layer bounds, reduced-motion alternatives, and the checks that confirm performance before claiming it.\n\n### When to Use\n\n- Choosing properties that stay on the compositor and avoid layout thrash.\n- Implementing layout-like transitions via FLIP or driving scroll-linked motion safely.\n- Bounding blur, filters, and promoted layers to protect memory and frame rate.\n- Providing a reduced-motion path that still communicates state, and verifying it.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Rendering Cost\n\n| Rendering step | Examples | Guidance |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Composite | `transform`, `opacity` | Default for reliable motion. |\n| Paint | color, border, shadow, filter, mask, image | Allowed for small, bounded, short-lived effects. |\n| Layout | width, height, top, left, margin, flow changes | Avoid continuous animation; use FLIP or structural alternatives. |\n\n## 3. Critical Never Patterns\n\n- Do not interleave layout reads and writes in the same frame.\n- Do not drive animation from `scrollTop`, `scrollY`, or raw scroll events.\n- Do not run `requestAnimationFrame` loops without a stop condition.\n- Do not mix multiple animation systems inside the same interaction surface.\n- Do not add `will-change` everywhere; use it temporarily and surgically, only on compositable properties (`transform`, `opacity`, `filter`), and never `will-change: all`.\n- Never use `transition: all`. Name the exact properties instead, for example `transition-property: transform, opacity`. `transition: all` animates unexpected properties and can trigger layout or paint work you never intended.\n\n## 4. FLIP Pattern\n\nFor layout-like transitions:\n1. Measure the first geometry.\n2. Apply the layout change.\n3. Measure the last geometry.\n4. Invert with transform.\n5. Play transform back to zero.\n\nThis makes the user perceive layout motion while the animation itself stays compositor-friendly.\n\n## 5. Scroll Motion\n\n- Use IntersectionObserver for visibility and pausing.\n- Use Scroll or View Timelines when the platform supports them.\n- Unobserve one-shot reveals after they run.\n- Avoid default fade-and-rise section reveals across an entire page.\n- Pause loops when off-screen.\n\n## 6. Blur, Filters, And Layers\n\n- Keep blur small, typically `<= 8px`, and short-lived.\n- Avoid continuous blur on large surfaces.\n- Isolate expensive effects with containment when possible.\n- Limit promoted layers; too many layers consume memory and can reduce performance.\n\n## 7. Reduced Motion\n\nReduced motion does not mean no state feedback. Replace movement with instant state changes, opacity shifts, color/focus changes, or static progress cues.\n\n```css\n@media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {\n  *, *::before, *::after {\n    animation-duration: 0.01ms !important;\n    animation-iteration-count: 1 !important;\n    transition-duration: 0.01ms !important;\n  }\n}\n```\n\nFor React motion, use `useReducedMotion()` and swap to `{ duration: 0 }` or a non-motion state.\n\n## 8. Verification\n\n- Test on the lowest target device, not only desktop Chrome.\n- Confirm no interaction is blocked during motion.\n- Confirm loops pause off-screen.\n- Confirm reduced-motion path communicates the same state.\n- Measure before claiming performance improved.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":100,"totalLines":100,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/references/performance_reduced_motion.md","time":{"start":1782532424877,"end":1782532424885}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_055e858694711a0b016a3f494896588191b1a99670617f62a5"}},"id":"prt_f07364497001UYSKo4NAZvyZUs","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","messageID":"msg_f0735f9390015P0CZVf1zX7dDY"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532424887,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_iK8cFcoEWNZW36BGawlElqfr","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/references/corpus_map.md","offset":1,"limit":220},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/references/corpus_map.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Motion Corpus Map\n3: description: Source-to-guidance map for temporal interaction design material distilled into motion.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"motion corpus\"\n6:   - \"animation source map\"\n7:   - \"temporal layer sources\"\n8: importance_tier: normal\n9: contextType: implementation\n10: version: 1.0.0.0\n11: ---\n12: \n13: # Motion Corpus Map\n14: \n15: This skill distills the temporal design corpus into practical, reusable motion guidance.\n16: \n17: ---\n18: \n19: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n20: \n21: ### Purpose\n22: \n23: Trace each piece of motion guidance back to its source corpus file and record where the distilled material now lives. This reference maps source files to the references they fed and states the distillation boundary between this skill and its siblings.\n24: \n25: ### When to Use\n26: \n27: - Confirming which corpus file a piece of motion guidance was distilled from.\n28: - Locating where a source topic now lives across the motion references.\n29: - Clarifying the boundary between motion build guidance, motion-performance review, and static systems.\n30: \n31: ---\n32: \n33: ## 2. Source Files\n34: \n35: | Corpus file | Distilled into | Practical guidance kept |\n36: | --- | --- | --- |\n37: | `external/animate.md` | `motion_strategy.md`, `performance_reduced_motion.md` | Purposeful motion, timing scale, easing, materials, perceived performance, reduced motion |\n38: | `external/interaction-design.md` | `micro_interactions.md`, `animate_presence_patterns.md` | Feedback patterns, loading, toggles, gestures, Framer Motion examples |\n39: | `external/delight.md` | `micro_interactions.md` | Earned delight, copy/personality boundaries, celebration and loading restraint |\n40: | `external/morphing-icons.md` | `micro_interactions.md` | Three-line SVG morphing architecture, collapsed lines, rotation groups, reduced-motion rules |\n41: | `external/12-principles-of-animation.md` | `motion_strategy.md`, `micro_interactions.md` | Timing, easing, physics (active/pressed state, subtle deformation), staging checks adapted for web UI |\n42: | `external/mastering-animate-presence.md` | `animate_presence_patterns.md` | Exit wrappers, exit props, keys, presence hooks, modes (sync/absolute remedy, popLayout for lists), nested exits |\n43: | `external/fixing-motion-performance.md` | `performance_reduced_motion.md` | Rendering steps glossary, critical never-patterns, FLIP measurement, blur bounds, will-change discipline, view transitions |\n44: | `external/make-interfaces-feel-better.md` | `micro_interactions.md`, `animate_presence_patterns.md`, `performance_reduced_motion.md` | Interruptible CSS transitions vs one-shot keyframes, scale-on-press, icon spring `bounce: 0`, `initial={false}` first-render suppression, never `transition: all` |\n45: \n46: ## 3. Distillation Boundary\n47: \n48: This child owns motion build guidance. Motion-performance review and severity findings live in `audit`; static systems live in `foundations`.\n\n(End of file - total 48 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Motion Corpus Map\ndescription: Source-to-guidance map for temporal interaction design material distilled into motion.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"motion corpus\"\n  - \"animation source map\"\n  - \"temporal layer sources\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Motion Corpus Map\n\nThis skill distills the temporal design corpus into practical, reusable motion guidance.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/references/corpus_map.md","text":"---\ntitle: Motion Corpus Map\ndescription: Source-to-guidance map for temporal interaction design material distilled into motion.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"motion corpus\"\n  - \"animation source map\"\n  - \"temporal layer sources\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Motion Corpus Map\n\nThis skill distills the temporal design corpus into practical, reusable motion guidance.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nTrace each piece of motion guidance back to its source corpus file and record where the distilled material now lives. This reference maps source files to the references they fed and states the distillation boundary between this skill and its siblings.\n\n### When to Use\n\n- Confirming which corpus file a piece of motion guidance was distilled from.\n- Locating where a source topic now lives across the motion references.\n- Clarifying the boundary between motion build guidance, motion-performance review, and static systems.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Source Files\n\n| Corpus file | Distilled into | Practical guidance kept |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| `external/animate.md` | `motion_strategy.md`, `performance_reduced_motion.md` | Purposeful motion, timing scale, easing, materials, perceived performance, reduced motion |\n| `external/interaction-design.md` | `micro_interactions.md`, `animate_presence_patterns.md` | Feedback patterns, loading, toggles, gestures, Framer Motion examples |\n| `external/delight.md` | `micro_interactions.md` | Earned delight, copy/personality boundaries, celebration and loading restraint |\n| `external/morphing-icons.md` | `micro_interactions.md` | Three-line SVG morphing architecture, collapsed lines, rotation groups, reduced-motion rules |\n| `external/12-principles-of-animation.md` | `motion_strategy.md`, `micro_interactions.md` | Timing, easing, physics (active/pressed state, subtle deformation), staging checks adapted for web UI |\n| `external/mastering-animate-presence.md` | `animate_presence_patterns.md` | Exit wrappers, exit props, keys, presence hooks, modes (sync/absolute remedy, popLayout for lists), nested exits |\n| `external/fixing-motion-performance.md` | `performance_reduced_motion.md` | Rendering steps glossary, critical never-patterns, FLIP measurement, blur bounds, will-change discipline, view transitions |\n| `external/make-interfaces-feel-better.md` | `micro_interactions.md`, `animate_presence_patterns.md`, `performance_reduced_motion.md` | Interruptible CSS transitions vs one-shot keyframes, scale-on-press, icon spring `bounce: 0`, `initial={false}` first-render suppression, never `transition: all` |\n\n## 3. Distillation Boundary\n\nThis child owns motion build guidance. Motion-performance review and severity findings live in `audit`; static systems live in `foundations`.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":48,"totalLines":48,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/references/corpus_map.md","time":{"start":1782532424879,"end":1782532424887}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_055e858694711a0b016a3f4948966081919f979bcdb835658f"}},"id":"prt_f073644ae001cAHTqQhiFphjzP","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c93ffeovEiyqk3ArIgPy","messageID":"msg_f0735f9390015P0CZVf1zX7dDY"}}
